# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: international-electrotechnical-commission
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Human habitation in Afghanistan dates to the Middle Paleolithic era.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Popularly referred to as the graveyard of empires, the land has witnessed numerous military campaigns, including those by the Persians, Alexander the Great, the Maurya Empire, Arab Muslims, the Mongols, the British, the Soviet Union, and a US-led coalition.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan also served as the source from which the Greco-Bactrians and the Mughals, among others, rose to form major empires.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Because of the various conquests and periods in both the Iranian and Indian cultural spheres, the area was a center for Zoroastrianism, Buddhism, Hinduism, and later Islam.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The modern state of Afghanistan began with the Durrani Empire in the 18th century under Ahmad Shah Durrani, although Dost Mohammad Khan is sometimes considered to be the founder of the first modern Afghan state.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan became a buffer state in the Great Game between the British Empire and the Russian Empire.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] From India, the British attempted to subjugate Afghanistan but were repelled in the First Anglo-Afghan War; the Second Anglo-Afghan War saw a British victory.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Following the Third Anglo-Afghan War in 1919, Afghanistan became free of foreign political hegemony, and emerged as the independent Kingdom of Afghanistan in 1926; this monarchy lasted almost half a century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Since the late 1970s, Afghanistan's history has been dominated by extensive warfare, including coups, invasions, insurgencies, and civil wars.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] This period of instability began in 1973 when King Zahir Shah was overthrown by his cousin Mohammad Daoud Khan, ending the monarchy and resulting in the establishment of the Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan became the President of Afghanistan, ruling as an autocrat.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In 1978 the conflict became a violent one when a communist revolution overthrew and assassinated Daoud Khan, establishing the socialist Democratic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Subsequent infighting prompted the Soviet Union to invade Afghanistan in 1979.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The *mujahideen* won against the Soviets in the Soviet–Afghan War, leading to the Soviets' withdrawal in 1989.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The ensuing civil war overthrew the socialist republic and established the Islamic State of Afghanistan through the Peshawar Accord, which could not remain in force and resulted in a second civil war between *mujahideen* factions in 1992.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban controlled most of the country by 1996, but their Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan received little international recognition before its overthrow in the 2001 US invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban returned to power in 2021 after capturing Kabul, ending the 2001–2021 war.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is widely unrecognized by the international community due to reported violations of human rights in Afghanistan, particularly regarding the treatment of women by the Taliban.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is rich in natural resources, including lithium, iron, zinc, and copper.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] It is the third largest producer of both saffron and cashmere.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The country is a member of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation and a founding member of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Due to the effects of war in recent decades, the country has dealt with high levels of terrorism, poverty, and child malnutrition.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remains among the world's least developed countries with its economic output per capita among the lowest of any country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Some scholars suggest that the root name *Afghān* is derived from the Sanskrit word *Aśvakan*, which was the name used for ancient inhabitants of the Hindu Kush.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] *Aśvakan* literally means "horsemen", "horse breeders", or "cavalrymen" (from *aśva*, the Sanskrit and Avestan words for "horse").
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Historically, the ethnonym *Afghān* was used to refer to ethnic Pashtuns.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Arabic and Persian form of the name, *Afġān*, was first attested in the 10th-century geography book *Hudud al-'Alam*.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The last part of the name, "*-stan*", is a Persian suffix meaning "place of".
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Therefore, "Afghanistan" translates to "land of the Afghans", or "land of the Pashtuns" in a historical sense.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The term "Afghanistan" was officially used in 1855, when the British recognized Dost Mohammad Khan as king of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Excavations of prehistoric sites suggest that humans were living in what is now Afghanistan at least 50,000 years ago, and that farming communities in the area were among the earliest in the world.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] An important site of early historical activities, many believe that Afghanistan compares to Egypt in the historical value of its archaeological sites.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Artifacts typical of the Paleolithic, Mesolithic, Neolithic, Bronze, and Iron Ages have been found in Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Urban civilization is believed to have begun as early as 3000 BCE, and the early city of Mundigak (near Kandahar in the south of the country) was a center of the Helmand culture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] More recent findings established that the Indus Valley Civilization stretched up towards modern-day Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] An Indus Valley site has been found on the Oxus River at Shortugai in northern Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] After 2000 BCE successive waves of semi-nomadic people from Central Asia began moving south into Afghanistan; among them were many Indo-European-speaking Indo-Iranians.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] These tribes later migrated further into South Asia, Western Asia, and toward Europe via the area north of the Caspian Sea.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The region at the time was referred to as Ariana.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] By the middle of the 6th century BCE, the Achaemenids overthrew the Medes and incorporated Arachosia, Aria, and Bactria within its eastern boundaries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] An inscription on the tombstone of Darius I of Persia mentions the Kabul Valley in a list of the 29 countries that he had conquered.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The region of Arachosia, around Kandahar in modern-day southern Afghanistan, used to be primarily Zoroastrian and played a key role in the transfer of the Avesta to Persia and is thus considered by some to be the "second homeland of Zoroastrianism".
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Alexander the Great and his Macedonian forces arrived in Afghanistan in 330 BCE after defeating Darius III of Persia a year earlier in the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Following Alexander's brief occupation, the successor state of the Seleucid Empire controlled the region until 305 BCE, when they gave much of it to the Maurya Empire as part of an alliance treaty.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Mauryans controlled the area south of the Hindu Kush until they were overthrown in about 185 BCE.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Their decline began 60 years after Ashoka's rule ended, leading to the Hellenistic reconquest by the Greco-Bactrians.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Much of it soon broke away and became part of the Indo-Greek Kingdom.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] They were defeated and expelled by the Indo-Scythians in the late 2nd century BCE.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Silk Road appeared during the first century BCE, and Afghanistan flourished with trade, with routes to China, India, Persia, and north to the cities of Bukhara, Samarkand, and Khiva in present-day Uzbekistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Goods and ideas were exchanged at this center point, such as Chinese silk, Persian silver and Roman gold, while the region of present Afghanistan was mining and trading lapis lazuli stones mainly from the Badakhshan region.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] During the first century BCE, the Parthian Empire subjugated the region but lost it to their Indo-Parthian vassals.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In the mid-to-late first century CE the vast Kushan Empire, centered in Afghanistan, became great patrons of Buddhist culture, making Buddhism flourish throughout the region.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Kushans were overthrown by the Sassanids in the 3rd century CE, though the Indo-Sassanids continued to rule at least parts of the region.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] They were followed by the Kidarites who, in turn, was replaced by the Hephthalites.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] They were replaced by the Turk Shahi in the 7th century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Buddhist Turk Shahi of Kabul was replaced by a Hindu dynasty before the Saffarids conquered the area in 870; this Hindu dynasty was called Hindu Shahi.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Much of the northeastern and southern areas of the country remained dominated by Buddhist culture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Arab Muslims brought Islam to Herat and Zaranj in 642 CE and began spreading eastward; some of the native inhabitants they encountered accepted it while others revolted.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Before the arrival of Islam, the region used to be home to various beliefs and cults, often resulting in Syncretism between the dominant religions such as Zoroastrianism, Buddhism or Greco-Buddhism, Ancient Iranian religions, Hinduism, Christianity, and Judaism.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] An exemplification of the syncretism in the region would be that people were patrons of Buddhism but still worshipped local Iranian gods such as Ahura Mazda, Lady Nana, Anahita or Mihr (Mithra) and portrayed Greek gods as protectors of Buddha.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Zunbils and Kabul Shahi were first conquered in 870 CE by the Saffarid Muslims of Zaranj.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Later, the Samanids extended their Islamic influence south of the Hindu Kush.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavids rose to power in the 10th century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] By the 11th century, Mahmud of Ghazni had defeated the remaining Hindu rulers and effectively Islamized the wider region, with the exception of Kafiristan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud made Ghazni into an important city and patronized intellectuals such as the historian al-Biruni and the poet Ferdowsi.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavid dynasty was overthrown by the Ghurids in 1186, whose architectural achievements included the remote Minaret of Jam.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Ghurids controlled Afghanistan for less than a century before being conquered by the Khwarazmian dynasty in 1215.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In 1219 CE, Genghis Khan and his Mongol army overran the region.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] His troops are said to have annihilated the Khwarazmian cities of Herat and Balkh as well as Bamyan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The destruction caused by the Mongols forced many locals to return to an agrarian rural society.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Mongol rule continued with the Ilkhanate in the northwest while the Khalji dynasty administered the Afghan tribal areas south of the Hindu Kush until the invasion of Timur (aka Tamerlane), who established the Timurid Empire in 1370.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Under the rule of Shah Rukh, the city of Herat served as the focal point of the Timurid Renaissance, whose glory matched Florence of the Italian Renaissance as the center of a cultural rebirth.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In the early 16th century Babur arrived from Ferghana and captured Kabul from the Arghun dynasty.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Babur would go on to conquer the Afghan Lodi dynasty who had ruled the Delhi Sultanate in the First Battle of Panipat.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Between the 16th and 18th century, the Uzbek Khanate of Bukhara, Iranian Safavids, and Indian Mughals ruled parts of the territory.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] During the medieval period, the northwestern area of Afghanistan was referred to by the regional name Khorasan, which was commonly used up to the 19th century among natives to describe their country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In 1709, Mirwais Hotak, a local Ghilzai tribal leader, successfully rebelled against the Safavids.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He defeated Gurgin Khan, the Georgian governor of Kandahar under the Safavids, and established his own kingdom.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Mirwais died in 1715, and was succeeded by his brother Abdul Aziz, who was soon killed by Mirwais's son Mahmud for possibly planning to sign a peace with the Safavids.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud led the Afghan army in 1722 to the Persian capital of Isfahan, and captured the city after the Battle of Gulnabad and proclaimed himself King of Persia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan dynasty was ousted from Persia by Nader Shah after the 1729 Battle of Damghan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In 1738, Nader Shah and his forces captured Kandahar in the siege of Kandahar, the last Hotak stronghold, from Shah Hussain Hotak.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Soon after, the Persian and Afghan forces invaded India, Nader Shah had plundered Delhi, alongside his 16-year-old commander, Ahmad Shah Durrani who had assisted him on these campaigns.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Ahmad Shah had launched two campaigns into Khorasan, 1750–1751 and 1754–1755.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] By the early 19th century, the Afghan empire was under threat from the Persians in the west and the Sikh Empire in the east.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan, leader of the Barakzai tribe, installed many of his brothers in positions of power throughout the empire.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan was brutally murdered in 1818 by Mahmud Shah.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] As a result, the brothers of Fateh Khan and the Barakzai tribe rebelled, and a civil war brewed.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] During this turbulent period, Afghanistan fractured into many states, including the Principality of Qandahar, Emirate of Herat, Khanate of Qunduz, Maimana Khanate, and numerous other warring polities.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The most prominent state was the Emirate of Kabul, ruled by Dost Mohammad Khan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Akbar Khan and the Afghan army failed to capture the Jamrud Fort from the Sikh Khalsa Army, but killed Sikh commander Hari Singh Nalwa, thus ending the Afghan-Sikh Wars.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In 1893, Abdur Rahman signed an agreement in which the ethnic Pashtun and Baloch territories were divided by the Durand Line, which forms the modern-day border between Pakistan and Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Shia-dominated Hazarajat and pagan Kafiristan remained politically independent until being conquered by Abdur Rahman Khan in 1891–1896.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He was known as the "Iron Amir" for his features and his ruthless methods against tribes.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He died in 1901, succeeded by his son, Habibullah Khan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] During the First World War, when Afghanistan was neutral, Habibullah Khan was met by officials of the Central Powers in the Niedermayer–Hentig Expedition.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] They called on Afghanistan to declare full independence from the United Kingdom, join them and attack British India, as part of the Hindu–German Conspiracy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The effort to bring Afghanistan into the Central Powers failed, but it sparked discontent among the population about maintaining neutrality with the British.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Habibullah was assassinated in February 1919, and Amanullah Khan eventually assumed power.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] A staunch supporter of the 1915–1916 expeditions, Amanullah Khan invaded British India, beginning the Third Anglo-Afghan War, and entering British India via the Khyber Pass.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Following the end of the Third Anglo-Afghan War and the signing of the Treaty of Rawalpindi on 19 August 1919, Emir Amanullah Khan declared the Emirate of Afghanistan a sovereign and fully independent state.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He moved to end his country's traditional isolation by establishing diplomatic relations with the international community, particularly with the Soviet Union and the Weimar Republic.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He proclaimed himself King of Afghanistan on 9 June 1926, forming the Kingdom of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He introduced several reforms intended to modernize his nation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] A key force behind these reforms was Mahmud Tarzi, an ardent supporter of the education of women.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He fought for Article 68 of Afghanistan's 1923 constitution, which implemented compulsory elementary education.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah's wife, Queen Soraya, was an important figure during this period in the fight for women's education and against their oppression.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Some of the reforms, such as the abolition of the traditional burqa for women and the opening of co-educational schools, alienated many tribal and religious leaders, leading to the Afghan Civil War (1928–1929).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah abdicated in January 1929, and soon after Kabul fell to Saqqawist forces led by Habibullah Kalakani.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Mohammad Nadir Shah, Amanullah's cousin, defeated and killed Kalakani in October 1929, and was declared King Nadir Shah.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He abandoned the reforms of King Amanullah in favor of a more gradual approach to modernization, but was assassinated in 1933 by Abdul Khaliq.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Mohammed Zahir Shah succeeded to the throne and reigned as king from 1933 to 1973.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] During the tribal revolts of 1944–1947, King Zahir's reign was challenged by Zadran, Safi, Mangal, and Wazir tribesmen led by Mazrak Zadran, Salemai, and Faqir of Ipi, among others – many of whom were Amanullah loyalists.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan joined the League of Nations in 1934.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In the 1930s, the country experienced significant development of roads, infrastructure, the founding of a national bank, and increased education.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Road links in the north played a large part in a growing cotton and textile industry.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The country built close relationships with the Axis powers, with Nazi Germany having the largest share in Afghan development at the time.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Until 1946, King Zahir ruled with the assistance of his uncle, who held the post of prime minister and continued the policies of Nadir Shah.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Another uncle, Shah Mahmud Khan, became prime minister in 1946 and experimented with allowing greater political freedom.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] He was replaced in 1953 by Mohammed Daoud Khan, a Pashtun nationalist who sought the creation of a Pashtunistan, leading to highly tense relations with Pakistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan pressed for social modernization reforms and sought a closer relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afterward, the 1964 constitution was formed, and the first non-royal prime minister was sworn in.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Zahir Shah, like his father Nadir Shah, had a policy of maintaining national independence while pursuing gradual modernization, creating nationalist feeling, and improving relations with the United Kingdom.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan was neither a participant in World War II nor aligned with either power bloc in the Cold War.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] However, it was a beneficiary of the latter rivalry as both the Soviet Union and the United States vied for influence by building Afghanistan's main highways, airports, and other vital infrastructure.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] On a per capita basis, Afghanistan received more Soviet development aid than any other country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In 1973, while the King was in Italy, Daoud Khan launched a bloodless coup and became the first president of Afghanistan, abolishing the monarchy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In April 1978, the communist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA) seized power in a bloody coup d'état against then-President Mohammed Daoud Khan, in what is called the Saur Revolution.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA declared the establishment of the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan, with its first leader named as People's Democratic Party General Secretary Nur Muhammad Taraki.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] This would trigger a series of events that would dramatically turn Afghanistan from a peaceful (albeit poor and secluded) country to a hotbed of conflict and terrorism.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA initiated various social, symbolic, and land distribution reforms that provoked strong opposition, while also brutally oppressing political dissidents.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] This caused unrest and quickly expanded into a state of civil war by 1979, waged by guerrilla *mujahideen* (and smaller Maoist guerrillas) against regime forces countrywide.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] It quickly turned into a proxy war as the Pakistani government provided these rebels with covert training centers, the United States supported them through Pakistan's Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), and the Soviet Union sent thousands of military advisers to support the PDPA regime.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Meanwhile, there was increasingly hostile friction between the competing factions of the PDPA – the dominant Khalq and the more moderate Parcham.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In October 1979, PDPA General Secretary Taraki was assassinated in an internal coup orchestrated by then-prime minister Hafizullah Amin, who became the new general secretary of the PDPA.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The situation in the country deteriorated under Amin, and thousands of people went missing.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Displeased with Amin's government, the Soviet Army invaded the country in December 1979, heading for Kabul and killing Amin.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] A Soviet-organized regime, led by Parcham's Babrak Karmal but inclusive of both factions (Parcham and Khalq), filled the vacuum.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Soviet troops in more substantial numbers were deployed to stabilize Afghanistan under Karmal, marking the beginning of the Soviet–Afghan War.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Lasting nine years, the war caused the deaths of between 562,000 and 2 million Afghans, and displaced about 6 million people who subsequently fled Afghanistan, mainly to Pakistan and Iran.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Heavy air bombardment destroyed many countryside villages, millions of landmines were planted, and some cities such as Herat and Kandahar were also damaged from bombardment.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] After the Soviet withdrawal, another civil war ensued until the communist regime under PDPA leader Mohammad Najibullah collapsed in 1992.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Soviet–Afghan War had drastic social effects on Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The militarization of society led to heavily armed police, private bodyguards, openly armed civil defense groups, and the like becoming the norm in Afghanistan for decades thereafter.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The traditional power structure had shifted from the clergy, community elders, intelligentsia, and military in favor of powerful warlords.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Another civil war broke out after the creation of a dysfunctional coalition government between leaders of various *mujahideen* factions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Amid a state of anarchy and factional infighting, various *mujahideen* factions committed widespread rape, murder, and extortion, while Kabul was heavily bombarded and partially destroyed by the fighting.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Several failed reconciliations and alliances occurred between different leaders.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban emerged in September 1994 as a movement and militia of students (*talib*) from Islamic madrassas (schools) in Pakistan, who soon had military support from Pakistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Taking control of Kandahar city that year, they conquered more territories until finally driving out the government of Rabbani from Kabul in 1996, where they established an emirate.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban were condemned internationally for the harsh enforcement of their interpretation of Islamic sharia law, which resulted in the brutal treatment of many Afghans, especially women.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] During their rule, the Taliban and their allies committed massacres against Afghan civilians, denied UN food supplies to starving civilians, and conducted a policy of scorched earth, burning vast areas of fertile land and destroying tens of thousands of homes.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] After the fall of Kabul to the Taliban, Ahmad Shah Massoud and Abdul Rashid Dostum formed the Northern Alliance, later joined by others, to resist the Taliban.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Dostum's forces were defeated by the Taliban during the Battles of Mazar-i-Sharif in 1997 and 1998; Pakistan's Chief of Army Staff, Pervez Musharraf, began sending thousands of Pakistani militants to help the Taliban defeat the Northern Alliance.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] By 2000, the Northern Alliance only controlled 10% of the territory, cornered in the northeast.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] On 9 September 2001, Massoud was assassinated by two Arab suicide attackers in Panjshir Valley.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Around 400,000 Afghans died in internal conflicts between 1990 and 2001.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In October 2001, the United States invaded Afghanistan to remove the Taliban from power after they refused to hand over Osama bin Laden, the prime suspect of the September 11 attacks, who was a "guest" of the Taliban and was operating his al-Qaeda network in Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The majority of Afghans supported the American invasion.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] During the initial invasion, US and UK forces bombed al-Qaeda training camps, and later, in cooperation with the Northern Alliance, the Taliban regime came to an end.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In December 2001, after the Taliban government was overthrown, the Afghan Interim Administration under Hamid Karzai was formed.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) was established by the United Nations Security Council to assist the Karzai administration and provide basic security.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] By this time, after two decades of war as well as an acute famine at the time, Afghanistan had one of the highest infant and child mortality rates in the world, the lowest life expectancy, much of the population suffered from hunger and malnutrition, and infrastructure was in ruins.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Many foreign donors started providing aid and assistance to rebuild the war-torn country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] As coalition troops entered Afghanistan to help the rebuilding process, the Taliban began an insurgency to regain control.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remained one of the poorest countries in the world because of a lack of foreign investment, government corruption, and the Taliban insurgency.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan government was able to establish some democratic structures, adopting a constitution in 2004 with the name Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Attempts were made, often with the support of foreign donor countries, to improve the country's economy, healthcare, education, transport, and agriculture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] ISAF forces also began to train the Afghan National Security Forces.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Following 2002, nearly five million Afghans were repatriated.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The number of NATO troops present in Afghanistan peaked at 140,000 in 2011, dropping to approximately 16,000 in 2018.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In September 2014, Ashraf Ghani became president after the 2014 Afghan presidential election, in which, for the first time in Afghanistan's history, power was democratically transferred.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] On 28 December 2014, NATO formally ended ISAF combat operations and transferred full security responsibility to the Afghan government.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The NATO-led Operation Resolute Support was formed the same day as a successor to ISAF.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Thousands of NATO troops remained in the country to train and advise Afghan government forces and continue their fight against the Taliban.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] A report titled *Body Count* concluded that 106,000–170,000 civilians had been killed as a result of the fighting in Afghanistan at the hands of all parties to the conflict.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] On 19 February 2020, the United States–Taliban deal was made in Qatar.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg announced on 14 April 2021 that the alliance had agreed to start withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan by 1 May.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Soon after NATO troops began withdrawing, the Taliban launched an offensive against the Afghan government and quickly advanced in front of collapsing Afghan government forces.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban captured the capital city of Kabul on 15 August 2021, after regaining control over a vast majority of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Several foreign diplomats and Afghan government officials, including President Ashraf Ghani, were evacuated from the country, with many Afghan civilians attempting to flee along with them.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] On 17 August, first vice president Amrullah Saleh proclaimed himself caretaker president and announced the formation of an anti-Taliban front with a reported 6,000+ troops in the Panjshir Valley, along with Ahmad Massoud.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] However, by 6 September, the Taliban had taken control of most of Panjshir Province, with resistance fighters retreating to the mountains.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Clashes in the valley ceased in mid-September.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] According to the Costs of War Project, 176,000 people were killed in the conflict, including 46,319 civilians, between 2001 and 2021.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] According to the Uppsala Conflict Data Program, at least 212,191 people were killed in the conflict.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Though the state of war in the country ended in 2021, armed conflict persists in some regions amid fighting between the Taliban and the local branch of the Islamic State, as well as an anti-Taliban Republican insurgency.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is led by supreme leader Hibatullah Akhundzada and acting prime minister Hasan Akhund, who took office on 7 September 2021.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Akhund is one of the four founders of the Taliban and was a deputy prime minister of the previous emirate; his appointment was seen as a compromise between moderates and hardliners.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] A new, all-male cabinet was formed, which included Abdul Hakim Haqqani as minister of justice.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] On 20 September 2021, United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres received a letter from acting minister of foreign affairs Amir Khan Muttaqi to formally claim Afghanistan's seat as a member state for their official spokesman in Doha, Suhail Shaheen.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The United Nations did not recognize the previous Taliban government and chose to work with the then government-in-exile instead.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Western nations suspended most of their humanitarian aid to Afghanistan following the Taliban's August 2021 takeover of the country; the World Bank and International Monetary Fund also halted their payments.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] More than half of Afghanistan's 39 million people faced an acute food shortage in October 2021.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Human Rights Watch reported on 11 November 2021 that Afghanistan was facing widespread famine due to an economic and banking crisis.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban initially significantly tackled corruption, improving on the corruption perceptions index from 174th to 150th out of 180 countries from 2021 to 2022, but dropping to 162nd in 2023.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban have also reportedly reduced bribery and extortion in public service areas.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] At the same time, the human rights situation in the country has deteriorated.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Following the 2001 invasion, more than 5.7 million refugees returned to Afghanistan; however, in 2021, 2.6 million Afghans remained refugees, primarily in Iran and Pakistan, and another 4 million were internally displaced.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In October 2023, the Pakistani government ordered the expulsion of Afghans from Pakistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Iran also decided to deport Afghan nationals back to Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Taliban authorities condemned the deportations of Afghans as an "inhuman act".
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan faced a humanitarian crisis in late 2023.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] On 10 November 2024, Afghanistan's Foreign Ministry confirmed that Taliban representatives would attend the 2024 United Nations Climate Change Conference, marking the first time the country participated since the Taliban's return to power in 2021.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had been barred from previous summits due to the lack of global recognition of the Taliban regime.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In May 2025, Iran ordered the mass deportation of an estimated 4 million Afghan migrants and refugees.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The 2025–2026 hunger crisis in Afghanistan is one of the world's most severe, with over 17 million people—one-third of the population—requiring urgent food assistance.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Driven by persistent drought, economic collapse, and massive refugee returns, the crisis has left over 4.9 million children and women needing malnutrition treatment.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is located in Southern-Central Asia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The region centered in Afghanistan is considered the "crossroads of Asia", and the country has had the nickname Heart of Asia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] At over 652,864 km2 (252,072 sq mi), Afghanistan is the world's 41st largest country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] It is slightly bigger than France and smaller than Myanmar, and about the size of Texas in the United States.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] There is no coastline, as Afghanistan is landlocked.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The geography in Afghanistan is varied, but is mostly mountainous and rugged, with some unusual mountain ridges accompanied by plateaus and river basins.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] It is dominated by the Hindu Kush range, the western extension of the Himalayas that stretches to eastern Tibet via the Pamir Mountains and Karakoram Mountains in Afghanistan's far north-east.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Most of the highest points are in the east, consisting of fertile mountain valleys, often considered part of the "Roof of the World".
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Hindu Kush ends at the west-central highlands, creating plains in the north and southwest, namely the Turkestan Plains and the Sistan Basin; these two regions consist of rolling grasslands and semi-deserts, as well as hot, windy deserts, respectively.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Forests exist in the corridor between the provinces of Nuristan and Paktika (see East Afghan montane conifer forests), and tundra in the northeast.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The country's highest point is Noshaq, at 7,492 m (24,580 ft) above sea level.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The lowest point is located in Jowzjan Province along the Amu River bank, at 258 m (846 ft) above sea level.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Despite having numerous rivers and reservoirs, large parts of the country are dry.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The endorheic Sistan Basin is one of the world's driest regions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Amu Darya rises in the north of the Hindu Kush, while the nearby Hari River flows west towards Herat, and the Arghandab River flows from the central region southwards.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] To the south and west of the Hindu Kush flow a number of streams that are tributaries of the Indus River, such as the Helmand River.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Kabul River flows in an easterly direction to the Indus, ending at the Indian Ocean.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan receives heavy snow during the winter in the Hindu Kush and Pamir Mountains, and the melting snow in the spring season enters the rivers, lakes, and streams.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] However, two-thirds of the country's water flows into the neighboring countries of Iran, Pakistan, and Turkmenistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] As reported in 2010, the state needs more than US$2 billion to rehabilitate its irrigation systems so that the water is properly managed.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In Afghanistan, forest cover accounts for approximately 2% of the total land area, equivalent to 1,208,440 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, which remained unchanged since 1990.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity), and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The northeastern Hindu Kush mountain range, located in and around the Badakhshan Province of Afghanistan, is situated in a geologically active area where earthquakes occur almost every year.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] They can be deadly and destructive, causing landslides in some parts or avalanches during the winter.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In June 2022, a destructive 5.9 earthquake struck near the border with Pakistan, killing at least 1,150 people and sparking fears of a major humanitarian crisis.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] On 7 October 2023, a 6.3 magnitude earthquake struck northwest of Herat, killing over 1,400 people.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The country is generally arid in the summers, with most rainfall falling between December and April.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The lower areas of northern and western Afghanistan are the driest, with precipitation more common in the east.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Although proximate to India, Afghanistan is mostly outside the monsoon zone, except the Nuristan Province, which occasionally receives summer monsoon rain.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Although Afghanistan has contributed minimally to global greenhouse gas emissions, it is one of the most vulnerable countries to climate change and least prepared to cope with its impacts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Climate change in Afghanistan is causing more frequent and severe droughts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Severe drought conditions affect 25 of the country's 34 provinces, impacting over half the population.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] These droughts cause desertification, reduce food and water security, disrupt agriculture, and cause internal displacement.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Extreme rainfall over short periods is also more likely, increasing the risk of floods and landslides.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Due to rising temperatures, almost 14% of Afghanistan's glacier coverage was lost between 1990 and 2015, increasing the risk of glacial lake outburst floods.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] By 2050, climate change could displace an additional 5 million people within Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Several types of mammals exist throughout Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Snow leopards and brown bears live in the high elevation alpine tundra regions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Marco Polo sheep exclusively live in the Wakhan Corridor region of north-east Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Foxes, wolves, otters, deer, wild sheep, lynx and other big cats populate the mountain forest region of the east.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] In the semi-desert northern plains, wildlife include a variety of birds, hedgehogs, gophers, and large carnivores such as jackals and hyenas.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Gazelles, wild pigs and jackals populate the steppe plains of the south and west, while mongoose and cheetahs exist in the semi-desert south.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Marmots and ibex also live in the high mountains of Afghanistan, and pheasants exist in some parts of the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan hound is a native breed of dog known for its fast speed and its long hair; it is relatively known in the west.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Endemic fauna of Afghanistan includes the Afghan flying squirrel, Afghan snowfinch, *Paradactylodon* (or the "Paghman mountain salamander"), *Stigmella kasyi*, *Vulcaniella kabulensis*, Afghan leopard gecko, *Wheeleria parviflorellus*, among others.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan has a wide variety of birds despite its relatively arid climate – an estimated 460 species of which 235 breed within.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The forest region of Afghanistan has vegetation such as pine trees, spruce trees, fir trees and larches, whereas the steppe grassland regions consist of broadleaf trees, short grass, perennial plants and shrublands.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] The colder high elevation regions are composed of hardy grasses and small flowering plants.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Several regions are designated protected areas; there are three national parks: Band-e Amir, Wakhan and Nuristan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 8.85/10, ranking it 15th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Following the effective collapse of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan during the 2021 Taliban offensive, the Taliban declared the country an Islamic Emirate.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] A new caretaker government was announced on 7 September.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only the Russian Federation has recognized the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan as the *de jure* government of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In the V-Dem Democracy Indices, Afghanistan ranks amongst the lowest as a "closed autocracy," ranking at 176th and 177th out of 179 countries in electoral democracy and liberal democracy indices respectively.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan operates on a centralised unitary form of government.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] A traditional instrument of governance in Afghanistan is the *loya jirga* (grand assembly), a Pashtun consultative meeting that was mainly organized for choosing a new head of state, adopting a new constitution, or to settle national or regional issue such as war.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Loya jirgas have been held since at least 1747, with the most recent one occurring from June to July 2022.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] President Ashraf Ghani, having fled the country during the Taliban advance to either Tajikistan or Uzbekistan, emerged in the United Arab Emirates and said that he supported such negotiations and was in talks to return to Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Many figures within the Taliban generally agreed that continuation of the 2004 Constitution of Afghanistan may, if correctly applied, be workable as the basis for the new religious state as their objections to the former government were political, and not religious.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Hours after the final flight of American troops left Kabul on 30 August, a Taliban official interviewed said that a new government would likely be announced as early as Friday 3 September after Jumu'ah.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] It was added that Hibatullah Akhundzada would be officially named Emir, with cabinet ministers being revealed at the Arg in an official ceremony.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Ghani Baradar would be named head of government as Prime Minister, while other important positions would go to Sirajuddin Haqqani and Mullah Yaqoob.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Beneath the supreme leader, day-to-day governance will be entrusted to the cabinet.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In a report by CNN-News18, sources said the new government was going to be governed similarly to Iran with Hibatullah Akhundzada as supreme leader similar to the role of Saayid Ali Khamenei, and would be based out of Kandahar.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Baradar or Yaqoob would be head of government as Prime minister.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The government's ministries and agencies will be under a cabinet presided over by the Prime Minister.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The Supreme Leader would preside over an executive body known as the Supreme Council with anywhere from 11 to 72 members.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Hakim Haqqani is likely to be promoted to Chief justice.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] According to the report, the new government will take place within the framework of an amended 1964 Constitution of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Government formation was delayed due to concerns about forming a broad-based government acceptable to the international community.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] It was later added however that the Taliban's Rahbari Shura, the group's leadership council was divided between the hardline Haqqani Network and moderate Abdul Ghani Baradar over appointments needed to form an "inclusive" government.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Reports claimed that this culminated in a skirmish which led to Baradar being injured and treated in Pakistan, however this was denied by Baradar himself.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As of early September 2021 the Taliban were planning the cabinet to be men-only.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Journalists and other human rights activists, mostly women, protested in Herat and Kabul, calling for women to be included.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The acting Cabinet announced on 7 September was men-only, and the Ministry of Women's Affairs was abolished.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only Russia has recognized the Taliban government as the legitimate authorities of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The U.N has stated that recognition was impossible so long as restrictions on female education and employment remained.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] On 16 September 2024, the Taliban suspended polio vaccination campaigns in Afghanistan, as reported by the United Nations, posing a significant risk to global polio eradication efforts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In a decree by Hibatullah Akhundzada on 15 August 2025, the description of the government as interim was dropped, with all ministers remaining in their posts, but on a permanent rather than acting basis.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is administratively divided into 34 provinces (*wilayat*).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Each province has a governor and a capital.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country is further divided into nearly 400 provincial districts, each of which normally covers a city or several villages.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Each district is represented by a district governor.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are now appointed by the Prime Minister of Afghanistan, and the district governors are selected by the provincial governors.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are representatives of the central government in Kabul and are responsible for all administrative and formal issues within their provinces.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] There are also provincial councils that are elected through direct and general elections for four years.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The functions of provincial councils are to take part in provincial development planning and to participate in the monitoring and appraisal of other provincial governance institutions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] According to article 140 of the constitution and the presidential decree on electoral law, mayors of cities should be elected through free and direct elections for a four-year term.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In practice however, mayors are appointed by the government.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan became a member of the United Nations in 1946.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Relations with Pakistan have often been tense for various reasons such as the Durand Line border issue and alleged Pakistani involvement in Afghan insurgent groups.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The present Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan is currently partially recognized, but has had notable unofficial ties with China, Pakistan, and Qatar.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Under the previous Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, it enjoyed cordial relations with a number of NATO and allied nations, particularly the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, and Turkey.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2012, the United States and the then-republic in Afghanistan signed their Strategic Partnership Agreement in which Afghanistan became a major non-NATO ally.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Such qualification was rescinded by US President Joe Biden in July 2022.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The Armed Forces of the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan captured a large amount of weapons, hardware, vehicles, aerocrafts, and equipment from the Afghan National Security Forces following the 2021 Taliban offensive and the Fall of Kabul.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The total value of the captured equipment has been estimated at US$83 billion.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Homosexuality is taboo in Afghan society; according to the Penal Code, homosexual intimacy is punished by up to a year in prison.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Under Sharia law offenders can be punished by death.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] However, an ancient tradition involving male homosexual acts between children and older men (typically wealthy warlords or elite people) called *bacha bazi* persists albeit punishable by the death penalty under Taliban law.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Religious minorities such as Sikhs, Hindus, and Christians have reportedly faced persecution.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Since May 2022, all women in Afghanistan have been required by law to wear full-body coverings when in public (either a burqa or an abaya paired with a niqāb, which leaves only the eyes uncovered).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] First Deputy Leader Sirajuddin Haqqani claimed the decree is only advisory and no form of hijab is compulsory in Afghanistan, though this contradicts the reality.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] It has been speculated that there is a genuine internal policy division over women's rights between hardliners, including leader Hibatullah Akhundzada, and pragmatists, though they publicly present a united front.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Another decree was issued shortly after the first, requiring female TV presenters to cover their faces during broadcasts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban takeover, suicides among women have become more common, and the country could now be one of the few where the rate of suicide among women surpasses that among men.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In May 2022, the Taliban dissolved Afghanistan's Human Rights Commission along with four other government departments, citing the country's budget deficit.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] ICC member states are obliged to arrest wanted persons if they are on their territory.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's nominal GDP was $20.1 billion in 2020, or $81 billion by purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Its GDP per capita is $2,459 (PPP) and $611 by nominal.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Despite having $1 trillion or more in mineral deposits, it remains one of the world's least developed countries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Its economic output per capita is among the lowest of any country as of 2026.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's rough physical geography and its landlocked status has been cited as reasons why the country has always been among the least developed in the modern era – a factor where progress is also slowed by contemporary conflict and political instability.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country imports over $7 billion worth of goods but exports only $784 million, mainly fruits and nuts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The service sector contributed the most to the GDP (55.9%) followed by agriculture (23%) and industry (21.1%).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Da Afghanistan Bank serves as the central bank of the nation and the Afghani (AFN) is the national currency, with an exchange rate of about 75 Afghanis to 1 US dollar.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] A number of local and foreign banks operate in the country, including the Afghanistan International Bank, New Kabul Bank, Azizi Bank, Pashtany Bank, Standard Chartered Bank, and the First Micro Finance Bank.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, one of the main drivers for the economic recovery was the return of over 5 million expatriates, who brought with them entrepreneurship and wealth-creating skills as well as much needed funds to start up businesses.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Many Afghans got involved in construction, which was one of the largest industries in the country at the time.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Some of the major national construction projects include the $35 billion New Kabul City next to the capital, the Aino Mena project in Kandahar, and the Ghazi Amanullah Khan Town near Jalalabad.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Similar development projects have also begun in Herat, Mazar-e-Sharif, and other cities.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] An estimated 400,000 people enter the labor market each year.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Several small companies and factories began operating in different parts of the country, which not only provide revenues to the government but also create new jobs.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Improvements to the business environment have resulted in more than $1.5 billion in telecom investment and created more than 100,000 jobs since 2003.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghan rugs are becoming popular again, allowing many carpet dealers around the country to hire more workers; in 2016–17 it was the fourth most exported group of items.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is a member of WTO, SAARC, ECO, and OIC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2018, a majority of imports come from either Iran, China, Pakistan and Kazakhstan, while 84% of exports are to Pakistan and India.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban's takeover of the country in August 2021, the United States has frozen about $9 billion in assets belonging to the Afghan central bank, blocking the Taliban from accessing billions of dollars held in US bank accounts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The GDP of Afghanistan is estimated to have dropped by 20% following the Taliban return to power.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Following this, after months of free-fall, the Afghan economy began stabilizing, as a result of the Taliban's restrictions on smuggled imports, limits on banking transactions, and UN aid.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2023, the Afghan economy began seeing signs of revival.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] This has also been followed by stable exchange rates, low inflation, stable revenue collection, and the rise of trade in exports.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In the third quarter of 2023, the Afghani rose to be the best performing currency in the world, climbing over 9% against the US dollar.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Agricultural production is the backbone of Afghanistan's economy and has traditionally dominated the economy, employing about 40% of the workforce as of 2018.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country is known for producing pomegranates, grapes, apricots, melons, and several other fresh and dry fruits.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan also became the world's top producer of cannabis in 2010.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In March 2023, however, cannabis production was banned by a decree from Hibatullah Akhundzada.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Saffron, the most expensive spice, grows in Afghanistan, particularly Herat Province.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In recent years, there has been an uptick in saffron production, which authorities and farmers are using to try to replace poppy cultivation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Between 2012 and 2019, the saffron cultivated and produced in Afghanistan was consecutively ranked the world's best by the International Taste and Quality Institute.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Production hit record high in 2019 (19,469 kg of saffron), and one kilogram is sold domestically between $634 and $1147.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The availability of cheap diesel-powered water pumps imported from China and Pakistan, and in the 2010s, of cheap solar power to pump water, resulted in expansion of agriculture and population in the southwestern deserts of Afghanistan in Kandahar, Helmand and Nimruz provinces in the 2010s.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Wells have gradually been deepened, but water resources are limited.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Opium is the major crop, but as of 2022, was under attack by the new Taliban government which, to suppress opium production, was systematically suppressing water pumping.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In a 2023 report, poppy cultivation in southern Afghanistan was reduced by over 80% as a result of Taliban campaigns to stop its use toward opium.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] This included a 99% reduction of opium growth in the Helmand Province.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In November 2023, a U.N report showed that in the entirety of Afghanistan, poppy cultivation dropped by over 95%, removing it from its place as being the world's largest opium producer.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country's natural resources include: coal, copper, iron ore, lithium, uranium, rare earth elements, chromite, gold, zinc, talc, barite, sulfur, lead, marble, precious and semi-precious stones, natural gas, and petroleum.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, US and Afghan government officials estimated that untapped mineral deposits located in 2007 by the US Geological Survey are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution estimated that if Afghanistan generates about $10 billion per year from its mineral deposits, its gross national product would double and provide long-term funding for critical needs.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The United States Geological Survey (USGS) estimated in 2006 that northern Afghanistan has an average 460 million m3 (2.9 billion bbl) of crude oil, 440 billion m3 (15.7 trillion cu ft) of natural gas, and 67 billion L (562 million US bbl) of natural gas liquids.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2011, Afghanistan signed an oil exploration contract with China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) for the development of three oil fields along the Amu Darya river in the north.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country has significant amounts of lithium, copper, gold, coal, iron ore, and other minerals.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The Khanashin carbonatite in Helmand Province contains 1,000,000 tonnes (980,000 long tons; 1,100,000 short tons) of rare earth elements.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2007, a 30-year lease was granted for the Aynak copper mine to the China Metallurgical Group for $3 billion, making it the biggest foreign investment and private business venture in Afghanistan's history.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The state-run Steel Authority of India won the mining rights to develop the huge Hajigak iron ore deposit in central Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Government officials estimate that 30% of the country's untapped mineral deposits are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] One official asserted that "this will become the backbone of the Afghan economy" and a Pentagon memo stated that Afghanistan could become the "Saudi Arabia of lithium".
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The lithium reserves of 21 Mio. tons could amount to the ones of Bolivia, which is currently viewed as the country with the largest lithium reserves.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Other larger deposits are the ones of bauxite and cobalt.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Access to biocapacity in Afghanistan is lower than world average.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2016, Afghanistan had 0.43 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, much less than the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2016 Afghanistan used 0.73 global hectares of biocapacity per person—their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] This means they use just under double as much biocapacity as Afghanistan contains.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As a result, Afghanistan is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In September 2023, the Taliban signed mining contracts worth $6.5 billion, with extractions based on gold, iron, lead, and zinc in the provinces of Herat, Ghor, Logar, and Takhar.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] According to the World Bank, 98% of the rural population have access to electricity in 2018, up from 28% in 2008.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As of 2016, Afghanistan produces 1,400 megawatts of power, but still imports the majority of electricity via transmission lines from Iran and the Central Asian states.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The majority of electricity production is via hydropower, helped by the amount of rivers and streams that flow from the mountains.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] However electricity is not always reliable and blackouts happen, including in Kabul.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In recent years an increasing number of solar, biomass and wind power plants have been constructed.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Currently under development are the CASA-1000 project which will transmit electricity from Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, and the Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India (TAPI) gas pipeline.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Power is managed by the Da Afghanistan Breshna Sherkat (DABS, Afghanistan Electricity Company).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Important dams include the Kajaki Dam, Dahla Dam, and the Sardeh Band Dam.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Tourism is a small industry in Afghanistan due to security issues.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Nevertheless, some 20,000 foreign tourists visit the country annually as of 2016.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In particular an important region for domestic and international tourism is the picturesque Bamyan Valley, which includes lakes, canyons and historical sites, helped by the fact it is in a safe area away from insurgent activity.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Smaller numbers visit and trek in regions such as the Wakhan Valley, which is also one of the world's most remote communities.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] From the late 1960s onwards, Afghanistan was a popular stop on the famous hippie trail, attracting many Europeans and Americans.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Coming from Iran, the trail traveled through various Afghan provinces and cities including Herat, Kandahar and Kabul before crossing to northern Pakistan, northern India, and Nepal.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Tourism peaked in 1977, the year before the start of political instability and armed conflict.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The city of Ghazni has significant history and historical sites, and together with Bamyan city have in recent years been voted Islamic Cultural Capital and South Asia Cultural Capital respectively.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The cities of Herat, Kandahar, Balkh, and Zaranj are also very historic.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The Minaret of Jam in the Hari River valley is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] A cloak reputedly worn by Islam's prophet Muhammad is kept in the Shrine of the Cloak in Kandahar, a city founded by Alexander the Great and the first capital of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The citadel of Alexander in the western city of Herat has been renovated in recent years and is a popular attraction.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In the north of the country is the Shrine of Ali, believed by many to be the location where Ali was buried.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The National Museum of Afghanistan in Kabul hosts a large number of Buddhist, Bactrian Greek and early Islamic antiquities; the museum suffered greatly by civil war but has been slowly restoring since the early 2000s.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Unexpectedly, tourism has seen improvement in Afghanistan following the Taliban takeover.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Active efforts by the Taliban encouraged tourism to increase from 691 tourists in 2021, to 2,300 in 2022, to 5,200 in 2023, with some estimates of between 7,000 and 10,000.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] This is, however, threatened by the Islamic State – Khorasan Province, who took responsibility for attacks on tourists, such as the 2024 Bamyan shooting.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Telecommunication services in Afghanistan are provided by Afghan Telecom, Afghan Wireless, Etisalat, MTN Group, and Roshan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country uses its own space satellite called Afghansat 1, which provides services to millions of phone, internet, and television subscribers.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] By 2001 following years of civil war, telecommunications was virtually a non-existent sector, but by 2016 it had grown to a $2 billion industry, with 22 million mobile phone subscribers and 5 million internet users.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The sector employs at least 120,000 people nationwide.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Due to Afghanistan's geography, transport between various parts of the country has historically been difficult.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The Ring Road is crucially important for domestic and international trade and the economy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] A key portion of the Ring Road is the Salang Tunnel, completed in 1964, which facilitates travel through the Hindu Kush mountain range and connects northern and southern Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] It is the only land route that connects Central Asia to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Several mountain passes allow travel between the Hindu Kush in other areas.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Serious traffic accidents are common on Afghan roads and highways, particularly on the Kabul–Kandahar and the Kabul–Jalalabad Road.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Traveling by bus in Afghanistan remains dangerous due to militant activities.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Air transport in Afghanistan is provided by the national carrier, Ariana Afghan Airlines, and by the private company Kam Air.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Airlines from a number of countries also provide flights in and out of the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] These include Air India, Emirates, Gulf Air, Iran Aseman Airlines, Pakistan International Airlines, and Turkish Airlines.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country has four international airports: Kabul International Airport (formerly Hamid Karzai International Airport), Kandahar International Airport, Herat International Airport, and Mazar-e Sharif International Airport.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Including domestic airports, there are 43.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Bagram Air Base is a major military airfield.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] These lines are used for freight only and there is no passenger service.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] A rail line between Khaf, Iran and Herat, western Afghanistan, intended for both freight and passengers, was under construction as of 2019.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] About 125 kilometres (78 mi) of the line will lie on the Afghan side.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Private vehicle ownership has increased substantially since the early 2000s.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Taxis are yellow and consist of both cars and auto rickshaws.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In rural Afghanistan, villagers often use donkeys, mules or horses to transport or carry goods.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Camels are primarily used by the Kochi nomads.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Bicycles are popular throughout Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan was estimated at 35.7 million as of 2024 by the Afghanistan National Statistics and Information Authority, whereas the UN estimates over 42.0 million.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 1979 the total population was reported to be about 15.5 million.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] About 25.3% are urbanite, 70.4% live in rural areas, and the remaining 4.3% are nomadic.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] An additional 3 million or so Afghans are temporarily housed in neighboring Pakistan and Iran, most of whom were born and raised in those two countries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As of 2013, Afghanistan was the largest refugee-producing country in the world, a title held for 32 years.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The current population growth rate is 2.37%, one of the highest in the world outside of Africa.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] This population is expected to reach 82 million by 2050 if current population trends continue.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan increased steadily until the 1980s, when civil war caused millions to flee to other countries such as Pakistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Millions have since returned and the war conditions contribute to the country having the highest fertility rate outside Africa.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's healthcare has recovered since the turn of the century, causing falls in infant mortality and increases in life expectancy, although it has the lowest life expectance of any country outside Africa.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] This (along with other factors such as returning refugees) caused rapid population growth in the 2000s that has only recently started to slow down.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan 2024 total fertility rate has been estimated at 4.4.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In 2022 it was 4.5, about twice the world average rate.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The rate has fallen since the early 1980s.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As estimated by the CIA World Factbook, 26% of the population was urbanized as of 2020.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] This is one of the lowest figures in the world; in Asia it is only higher than Cambodia, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization has increased rapidly, particularly in the capital Kabul, due to returning refugees from Pakistan and Iran after 2001, internally displaced people, and rural migrants.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization in Afghanistan is different from typical urbanization in that it is centered on just a few cities.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Kabul is the largest city, with a population of 5 million.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The other large cities are located generally in the "ring" around the Central Highlands, namely Kandahar in the south, Herat in the west, Mazar-i-Sharif, Kunduz in the north, and Jalalabad in the east.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghans are divided into several ethnolinguistic groups.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] According to research data by several institutions in 2019, the Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group, comprising 42%, followed by Tajiks, comprising 27% of the country's population.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The other two major ethnic groups are the Hazaras and Uzbeks, each at 9%.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] A further 10 other ethnic groups are recognized and each are represented in the Afghan National Anthem.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Dari and Pashto are the official languages of Afghanistan; bilingualism is very common.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Dari, which is also referred to as Eastern Persian as it is a variety of and mutually intelligible with Persian (and very often called 'Farsi' by some Afghans like in Iran), functions as the lingua franca in Kabul as well as in much of the northern and northwestern parts of the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Native speakers of Dari, of any ethnicity, are sometimes called Farsiwans.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Pashto is the native tongue of the Pashtuns, although many of them are also fluent in Dari while some non-Pashtuns are fluent in Pashto.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Despite the Pashtuns having been dominant in Afghan politics for centuries, Dari remained the preferred language for government and bureaucracy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] According to CIA World Factbook, Dari Persian is spoken by 78% (L1 + L2) and functions as the lingua franca, while Pashto is spoken by 50%, Uzbek 10%, English 5%, Turkmen 2%, Urdu 2%, Pashayi 1%, Nuristani 1%, Arabic 1%, and Balochi 1% (2021 est).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Data represent the most widely spoken languages; shares sum to more than 100% because there is much bilingualism in the country and because respondents were allowed to select more than one language.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] There are a number of smaller regional languages, including Uzbek, Turkmen, Balochi, Pashayi, and Nuristani.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] When it comes to foreign languages among the populace, many are able to speak or understand Hindustani (Urdu-Hindi), partly due to returning Afghan refugees from Pakistan and the popularity of Bollywood films respectively.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] English is also understood by some of the population, and has been gaining popularity as of the 2000s.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Some Afghans retain some ability in Russian, which was taught in public schools during the 1980s.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The CIA estimated in 2009 that 99.7% of the Afghan population was Muslim and most are thought to adhere to the Sunni Hanafi school.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] According to Pew Research Center, as much as 90% are of the Sunni denomination, 7% Shia and 3% non-denominational.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Conversion away from Islam is persecuted, limiting religious freedom.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Sikhs and Hindus are also found in certain major cities (namely Kabul, Jalalabad, Ghazni, Kandahar) accompanied by gurdwaras and mandirs.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] According to Deutsche Welle in September 2021, 250 remain in the country after 67 were evacuated to India.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] There was a small Jewish community in Afghanistan, living mainly in Herat and Kabul.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Over the years, this small community was forced to leave due to decades of warfare and religious persecution.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] By the end of the twentieth century, nearly the entire community had emigrated to Israel and the United States, with one known exception, Herat-born Zablon Simintov.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] He remained for years, being the caretaker of the only remaining Afghan synagogue.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] He left the country for the US after the second Taliban takeover.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] A woman who left shortly after him has since been identified as the likely last Jew in Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Christians, who number 500–8,000, practice their faith secretly due to intense societal opposition, and there are no public churches.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Education in Afghanistan is overseen by the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Higher Education.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] There are over 16,000 schools in the country and roughly 9 million students.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Of this, about 60% are males and 40% females.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] However, the new regime has thus far forbidden female teachers and female students from returning to secondary schools.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Over 174,000 students are enrolled in different universities around the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Former Education Minister Ghulam Farooq Wardak had stated that construction of 8,000 schools is required for the remaining children who are deprived of formal learning.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As of 2018 the literacy rate of the population age 15 and older is 43.02% (males 55.48% and females 29.81%).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The top universities in Afghanistan are the American University of Afghanistan (AUAF) followed by Kabul University (KU), both of which are located in Kabul.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The National Military Academy of Afghanistan, modeled after the United States Military Academy at West Point, was a four-year military development institution dedicated to graduating officers for the Afghan Armed Forces.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The Afghan Defense University was constructed near Qargha in Kabul.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Major universities outside of Kabul include Kandahar University in the south, Herat University in the northwest, Balkh University and Kunduz University in the north, Nangarhar University and Khost University in the east.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] After the Taliban regained power in 2021, it became unclear to what extent female education would continue in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In March 2022, after they had been closed for some time, it was announced that secondary education would be reopened shortly.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] However, shortly before reopening, the order was rescinded and schools for older girls remained closed.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Despite the ban, six provinces, Balkh, Kunduz, Jowzjan, Sar-I-Pul, Faryab, and the Day Kundi, still allow girls' schools from grade 6 and up.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In December 2023, investigations were being held by the United Nations on the claim that Afghan girls of all ages were allowed to study at religious schools.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] As of November 2024, some parts of the country allow women to attend religious schools to pursue dentistry, nursing, and other subjects.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] According to the Human Development Index, Afghanistan is the 15th least developed country in the world.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The average life expectancy is estimated to be around 60 years.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country's maternal mortality rate is 396 deaths/100,000 live births and its infant mortality rate is 66 to 112.8 deaths in every 1,000 live births.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The Ministry of Public Health plans to cut the infant mortality rate to 400 for every 100,000 live births before 2020.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The country has more than 3,000 midwives, with an additional 300 to 400 being trained each year.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] There are over 100 hospitals in Afghanistan, with the most advanced treatments being available in Kabul.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The French Medical Institute for Children and Indira Gandhi Children's Hospital in Kabul are the leading children's hospitals in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Some of the other leading hospitals in Kabul include the Jamhuriat Hospital and Jinnah Hospital.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] In spite of all this, many Afghans travel to Pakistan and India for advanced treatment.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] It was reported in 2006 that nearly 60% of the Afghan population lives within a two-hour walk of the nearest health facility.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] The disability rate is also high in Afghanistan due to the decades of war.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] It was reported recently that about 80,000 people are missing limbs.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p02] Non-governmental charities such as Save the Children and Mahboba's Promise assist orphans in association with governmental structures.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have both common cultural features and those that differ between the regions of Afghanistan, each with distinctive cultures partly as a result of geographic obstacles that divide the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Family is the mainstay of Afghan society and families are often headed by a patriarch.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] In the southern and eastern region, the people live according to the Pashtun culture by following Pashtunwali (the Pashtun way).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Key tenets of Pashtunwali include hospitality, the provision of sanctuary to those seeking refuge, and revenge for the shedding of blood.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Pashtuns are largely connected to the culture of Central Asia and the Iranian Plateau.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The remaining Afghans are culturally Persian and Turkic.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Some non-Pashtuns who live in proximity with Pashtuns have adopted Pashtunwali in a process called Pashtunization, while some Pashtuns have been Persianized.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Those who have lived in Pakistan and Iran over the last 30 years have been further influenced by the cultures of those neighboring nations.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan people are known to be strongly religious.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghans, particularly Pashtuns, are noted for their tribal solidarity and high regard for personal honor.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] There are various Afghan tribes, and an estimated 2–3 million nomads.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghan culture is deeply Islamic, but pre-Islamic practices persist.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Child marriage is prevalent; in 2017, Human Rights Watch described the legal age for marriage of girls as being 16, or 15 with the consent of the father or a judge.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The most preferred marriage in Afghan society is to one's parallel cousin, and the groom is often expected to pay a bride price.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] In the villages, families typically occupy mudbrick houses, or compounds with mudbrick or stone walled houses.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Villages typically have a headman (*malik*), a master for water distribution (*mirab*) and a religious teacher (*mullah*).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Men would typically work on the fields, joined by women during harvest.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] About 15% of the population are nomadic, locally called *kochis*.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] When nomads pass villages they often buy supplies such as tea, wheat and kerosene from the villagers; villagers buy wool and milk from the nomads.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghan clothing for both men and women typically consists of various forms of shalwar kameez, especially *perahan tunban* and *khet partug*.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Women would normally wear a *chador* for head covering; some women, typically from highly conservative communities, wear the *burqa*, a full body covering.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] These were worn by some women of the Pashtun community well before Islam came to the region, but the Taliban enforced this dress on women when they were in power.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Another popular dress is the *chapan* which acts as a coat.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The *karakul* is a hat made from the fur of a specific regional breed of sheep.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] It was favored by former kings of Afghanistan and became known to much of the world in the 21st century when it was constantly worn by President Hamid Karzai.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The *pakol* is another traditional hat originating from the far east of the country; it was popularly worn by the guerrilla leader Ahmad Shah Massoud.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The *Mazari hat* originates from northern Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The nation has a complex history that has survived either in its current cultures or in the form of various languages and monuments.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan contains many remnants from all ages, including Greek and Buddhist stupas, monasteries, monuments, temples, and Islamic minarets.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Among the most well known are the Great Mosque of Herat, the Blue Mosque, the Minaret of Jam, the Chil Zena, the Qala-i Bost in Lashkargah, the ancient Greek city of Ai-Khanoum.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] However, many of its historic monuments have been damaged in modern times due to the civil wars.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The two famous Buddhas of Bamiyan were destroyed by the Taliban, who regarded them as idolatrous.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] As there was no colonialism in the modern era in Afghanistan, European-style architecture is rare but does exist: the Victory Arch at Paghman and the Darul Aman Palace in Kabul were built in this style in the 1920s.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghan architecture also ranges deep into India such as the city of Agra, and the tomb of Sher Shah Suri, an Afghan Emperor of India.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Carpet weaving is an ancient practice in Afghanistan, and many of these are still handmade by tribal and nomadic people today.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Carpets have been produced in the region for thousands of years and traditionally done by women.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Some crafters express their feelings through the designs of rugs; for example after the outbreak of the Soviet–Afghan War, "war rugs", a variant of Afghan rugs, were created with designs representing pain and misery caused by the conflict.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Every province has its own specific characteristics in making rugs.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] In some of the Turkic-populated areas in the north-west, bride and wedding ceremony prices are driven by the bride's weaving skills.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Pottery has been crafted in Afghanistan for millennia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The village of Istalif, north of Kabul, is in particular a major center, known for its unique turquoise and green pottery, and their methods of crafting have remained the same for centuries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Much of *lapis lazuli* stones were earthed in modern-day Afghanistan which were used in Chinese porcelain as cobalt blue, later used in ancient Mesopotamia and Turkey.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The lands of Afghanistan have a long history of art, with the world's earliest known usage of oil painting found in cave murals in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] A notable art style that developed in Afghanistan and eastern Pakistan is Gandhara Art, produced by a fusion of Greco-Roman art and Buddhist art between the 1st and 7th centuries CE.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Later eras saw increased use of the Persian miniature style, with Kamaleddin Behzad of Herat being one of the most notable miniature artists of the Timurid and early Safavid periods.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Since the 1900s, the nation began to use Western techniques in art.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Abdul Ghafoor Breshna was a prominent Afghan painter and sketch artist from Kabul during the 20th century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Classic Persian and Pashto poetry are a cherished part of Afghan culture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Poetry has always been one of the major educational pillars in the region, to the level that it has integrated itself into culture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] One of the poetic styles is called landay.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] A popular theme in Afghan folklore and mythology are Divs, monstrous creatures.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Thursdays are traditionally "poetry night" in the city of Herat when men, women and children gather and recite both ancient and modern poems.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Pashto literature, although quantitatively remarkable and in great growth in the last century, has always had an essentially local meaning and importance, feeling the influence of both Persian literature and the contiguous literatures of India.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Both main literatures, from the second half of the nineteenth century, have shown themselves to be sensitive to genres, movements and stylistic features imported from Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Khushal Khan Khattak of the 17th century is considered the national poet.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Other notable poets include Rabi'a Balkhi, Jami, Rahman Baba, Khalilullah Khalili, and Parween Pazhwak.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghan classical music has close historical links with Indian classical music and use the same Hindustani terminology and theories like raga.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Genres of this style of music include ghazal (poetic music) and instruments such as the Indian tabla, sitar and harmonium, and local instruments like zerbaghali, as well as dayereh and tanbur which are also known in Central Asia, the Caucasus and the Middle East.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The rubab is the country's national instrument and precurses the Indian sarod instrument.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Some of the famous artists of classical music include Ustad Sarahang and Sarban.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Pop music developed in the 1950s through Radio Kabul and was influential in social change.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] During this time female artists also started appearing, at first Mermon Parwin.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Perhaps the most famous artist of this genre was Ahmad Zahir, who synthesized many genres and continues to be renowned for his voice and rich lyrics long after his death in 1979.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Other notable masters of traditional or popular Afghan music include Nashenas, Ubaidullah Jan, Mahwash, Ahmad Wali, Farhad Darya, and Naghma.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Attan is the national dance of Afghanistan, a group dance popularly performed by Afghans of all backgrounds.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The dance is considered part of Afghan identity.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan has around 350 radio stations and over 200 television stations.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Radio Television Afghanistan, originating from 1925, is the state public broadcaster.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Television programs began airing in the 1970s and today there are many private television channels such as TOLO and Shamshad TV.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The first Afghan newspaper was published in 1873, and there are hundreds of print outlets today.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] By the 1920s, Radio Kabul was broadcasting local radio services.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Voice of America, BBC, and Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty (RFE/RL) broadcast in both of Afghanistan's official languages on radio.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Press restrictions have been gradually relaxed and private media diversified since 2002, after more than two decades of tight controls.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghans have long been accustomed to watching Indian Bollywood films and listening to its filmi songs.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] It has been claimed that Afghanistan is among the biggest markets for the Hindi film industry.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The stereotypes of Afghans in India (*Kabuliwala* or *Pathani*) have also been represented in some Bollywood films by actors.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Many Bollywood film stars have roots in Afghanistan, including Salman Khan, Saif Ali Khan, Aamir Khan, Feroz Khan, Kader Khan, Naseeruddin Shah, Zarine Khan, Celina Jaitly, and a number of others.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Several Bollywood films have been shot inside Afghanistan, including *Dharmatma*, *Khuda Gawah*, *Escape from Taliban*, and *Kabul Express*.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghan cuisine is largely based upon the nation's chief crops, such as wheat, maize, barley and rice.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Accompanying these staples are native fruits and vegetables as well as dairy products such as milk, yogurt, and whey.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Kabuli palaw is the national dish of Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The nation's culinary specialties reflect its ethnic and geographic diversity.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan is known for its high-quality pomegranates, grapes, and sweet melons.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] A typical Afghan diet consists of naan, yogurt, rice, and meat.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Afghanistan's official New Year starts with Nowruz (natively known as "*Nawroz*"), an ancient tradition that started as a Zoroastrian celebration in present-day Iran, and with which it shares the annual celebration along with several other countries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] It occurs every year at the vernal equinox.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] In Afghanistan, Nowruz is typically celebrated with music and dance, as well as holding buzkashi tournaments.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Yaldā, another nationally celebrated ancient tradition, commemorates the ancient goddess Mithra and marks the longest night of the year on the eve of the winter solstice (*Čilli-yi Zimistān*; usually falling on 20 or 21 December), during which families gather together to recite poetry and eat fruit.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] As a predominantly Muslim country, Islamic events and festivals such as Ramadan, Eid al-Fitr and Ashura are widely celebrated annually in Afghanistan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Sikh festival of Vaisakhi is celebrated by the Sikh community and the Hindu festival Diwali by the Hindu community.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] National Independence Day is celebrated on 19 August to mark the Anglo-Afghan Treaty of 1919 and the country's full independence.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Several international celebrations are also officially held in Afghanistan, such as International Workers' Day, and International Women's Day.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Some regional festivals include the Red Flower Festival (during Nowruz) in Mazar-i-Sharif, and the Damboora Festival in Bamyan Province.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Sport in Afghanistan is managed by the Afghan Sports Federation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Cricket and association football are the two most popular sports in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Sports Federation promotes cricket, association football, basketball, volleyball, golf, handball, boxing, taekwondo, weightlifting, bodybuilding, track and field, skating, bowling, snooker, chess, and other sports.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national basketball team won the first team sports title at the 2010 South Asian Games.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] In 2012, the country's 3x3 basketball team won the gold medal at the 2012 Asian Beach Games.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] In 2013, Afghanistan's football team followed as it won the SAFF Championship.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan national cricket team, which was formed in 2001, won the 2009–10 ICC Intercontinental Cup.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The team played in the 2015, 2019, and 2023 Cricket World Cups.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) is the official governing body of the sport and is based in Kabul.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Alokozay Kabul International Cricket Ground serves as the nation's main cricket stadium.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] There are several other stadiums throughout the country, including the Ghazi Amanullah Khan International Cricket Stadium near Jalalabad.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] Domestically, cricket is played between teams from different provinces.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Afghanistan national football team has been competing in international football since 1941.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The national team plays its home games at the Ghazi Stadium in Kabul, while football in Afghanistan is governed by the Afghanistan Football Federation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The national team has never competed or qualified for the FIFA World Cup but won an international football trophy in 2013.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The country also has a national team in the sport of futsal, a 5-a-side variation of football.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The traditional and the national sport of Afghanistan is buzkashi, particularly popular in the north.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] It is similar to polo, played by horsemen in two teams, each trying to grab and hold a goat carcass.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/afghanistan-p03] The Afghan Hound (a type of running dog) originated in Afghanistan and was used in wolf hunting.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania was inhabited by several Illyrian tribes, among them the Ardiaei, Bylliones, Dassaretii, Enchele, and Taulantians, with the Chaonians settled in the southwest.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Several colonies were founded by the Ancient Greeks along the Albanian coast, most notably Apollonia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Illyrians were the dominant power in Albania before the rise of Macedon.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Following the Illyrian Wars, Albania was integrated into the Roman Empire and remained in the Byzantine Empire after its partition.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] During the Middle Ages, several Albanian principalities emerged, most notably the Principality of Arbanon, Kingdom of Albania, Principality of Albania and Albania Veneta.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In the 15th century, Albania became a center of resistance against Ottoman expansion under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, whose military campaigns repelled Ottoman advances for over two decades.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Although incorporated into the Ottoman Empire, Albania retained distinct cultural and social identities throughout four centuries of foreign rule, culminating in the Albanian Renaissance in the 19th century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania declared independence in 1912, followed by a turbulent 20th century marked by monarchy, foreign occupation during both World Wars, and a communist regime under Enver Hoxha.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Since its independence in 1912, Albania has undergone a number of political changes, transitioning from a monarchy to a communist regime before becoming a sovereign parliamentary constitutional republic.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Governed by a constitution prioritising the separation of powers, the country's political structure includes a parliament, a ceremonial president, a functional prime minister and a hierarchy of courts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania is a developing country with an upper-middle income economy driven by the service sector, with manufacturing and tourism, which attracted over 11 million visitors in 2024, also playing significant roles.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The illegal drug trade in Albania contributes around US$100 million to the economy per year.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] After the dissolution of its communist system, the country shifted from centralised planning to an open market economy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albanian citizens have universal health care access and free primary and secondary education.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The country is an official candidate for membership in the European Union, and has been negotiating accession since 2022.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The origin of the name "Albania" can be traced back to medieval Latin and the association with the Illyrian tribe of the Albani.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] This connection is further supported by the writings of the Ancient Greek geographer Ptolemy during the 2nd century AD, where he included the settlement of Albanopolis situated to the northeast of Durrës.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The presence of a medieval settlement named Albanon or Arbanon hints at the possibility of historical continuity.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The precise relationship between these historical references and the question of whether Albanopolis was synonymous with Albanon remain subjects of scholarly debate.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Byzantine historian Michael Attaliates, in his 11th-century historical account, provides the earliest undisputed reference to the Albanians, when he mentions them as participants in a revolt against Constantinople in 1079.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] He also identifies the Arbanitai as subjects of the Duke of Dyrrachium.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In the Middle Ages, Albania was denoted as *Arbëri* or *Arbëni* by its inhabitants, who identified themselves as *Arbëreshë* or *Arbëneshë*.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albanians employ the terms *Shqipëri* or *Shqipëria* for their nation, designations that trace their historical origins to the 14th century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] But only in the late 17th and early 18th centuries did these terms gradually supersede *Arbëria* and *Arbëreshë* among Albanians.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] These two expressions are widely interpreted to symbolise "Children of the Eagles" and "Land of the Eagles".
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Mesolithic habitation in Albania has been evidenced in several open-air sites which were close to the Adriatic coastline and in caves.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Mesolithic objects found in a cave near Xarrë include flint and jasper objects along with fossilised animal bones, while those discoveries at Mount Dajt comprise bone and stone tools similar to those of the Aurignacian culture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Neolithic era in Albania began around 7000 BC and is evidenced in finds which indicate domestication of sheep and goats and small-scale agriculture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] A part of the Neolithic population may have been the same as the Mesolithic population of the southern Balkans, like in the Konispol cave, where the Mesolithic stratum co-exists with Pre-Pottery Neolithic finds.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Cardium pottery culture appears in coastal Albania and across the Adriatic after 6500 BC, while the settlements of the interior took part in the processes that formed the Starčevo culture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Albanian bitumen mines of Selenicë provide early evidence of bitumen exploitation in Europe, dating to Late Neolithic Albania (from 5000 BC), when local communities used it as pigment for ceramic decoration, waterproofing, and adhesive for repairing broken vessels.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The bitumen of Selenicë circulated towards eastern Albania from the early 5th millennium BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] First evidence of its overseas trade export comes from the Neolithic and Bronze Age southern Italy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The high-quality bitumen of Selenicë has been exploited throughout all the historical ages since the Late Neolithic era until today.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Indo-Europeanisation of Albania in the context of the IE-isation of the western Balkans began after 2800 BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The presence of the Early Bronze Age tumuli in the vicinity of later Apollonia dates to 2679±174 calBC (2852–2505 calBC).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] These burial mounds belong to the southern expression of the Adriatic-Ljubljana culture (related to the later Cetina culture), which moved southwards along the Adriatic from the northern Balkans.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The same community built similar mounds in Montenegro (Rakića Kuće) and northern Albania (Shtoj).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The first archaeogenetic find related to the IE-isation of Albania involves a man with predominantly Yamnaya ancestry buried in a tumulus of northeastern Albania, which dates to 2663–2472 calBC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] During the Middle Bronze Age, Cetina culture sites and finds appear in Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Cetina culture moved southwards across the Adriatic from the Cetina valley of Dalmatia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The incorporated territory of Albania was historically inhabited by Indo-European peoples, amongst them numerous Illyrian and Epirote tribes.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The territory referred to as Illyria corresponded roughly to the area east of the Adriatic Sea in the Mediterranean Sea, extending in the south to the mouth of the Vjosë.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The first account of the Illyrian groups comes from the Periplus of the Euxine Sea, a Greek text written in the 4th century BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Bryges were also present in central Albania, while the south was inhabited by the Epirote Chaonians, whose capital was at Phoenice.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Other colonies, such as Apollonia and Epidamnos, were established by Greek city-states on the coast by the 7th century BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Illyrian Taulanti were a powerful Illyrian tribe among the earliest recorded tribes in the area.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] They lived in an area that corresponds with much of present-day Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Together with the Dardanian ruler Cleitus, Glaucias, the ruler of the Taulantian kingdom, fought against Alexander the Great at the Battle of Pelium in 335 BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] As time passed, the ruler of Ancient Macedonia, Cassander of Macedon, captured Apollonia and crossed the river Genusus (Albanian: *Shkumbin*) in 314 BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] A few years later, Glaucias laid siege to Apollonia and captured the Greek colony of Epidamnos.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Illyrian Ardiaei tribe, centred in Montenegro, ruled over most of the territory of northern Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Their Ardiaean Kingdom reached its greatest extent under King Agron, the son of Pleuratus II.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Agron extended his rule over other neighbouring tribes as well.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Following Agron's death in 230 BC, his wife, Teuta, inherited the Ardiaean kingdom.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Teuta's forces extended their operations further southwards to the Ionian Sea.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 229 BC, Rome declared war on the kingdom for extensively plundering Roman ships.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The war ended in an Illyrian defeat in 227 BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Teuta was eventually succeeded by Gentius in 181 BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Gentius clashed with the Romans in 168 BC, initiating the Third Illyrian War.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The conflict resulted in the Roman conquest of the region by 167 BC.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Romans split the region into three administrative divisions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Roman Empire was split in 395 upon the death of Theodosius I into an Eastern and Western Roman Empire, in part because of the increasing pressure from threats during the Barbarian Invasions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] From the 6th century into the 7th century, the Slavs crossed the Danube and largely absorbed the indigenous Greeks, Illyrians, and Thracians in the Balkans; thus, the Illyrians were mentioned for the last time in historical records in the 7th century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In the 11th century, the Great Schism formalised the break of communion between the Eastern Orthodox and Western Catholic Church, which is reflected in Albania through the emergence of a Catholic north and Orthodox south.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Albanian people inhabited the west of Lake Ochrida and the upper valley of the River Shkumbin and established the Principality of Arbanon in 1190 under the leadership of Progon of Kruja.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The realm was succeeded by his sons Gjin Progoni and Demetrio Progoni.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Upon the death of Dhimiter, the territory came under the rule of the Albanian-Greek Gregorios Kamonas and subsequently under the Golem of Kruja.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In the 13th century, the principality was dissolved.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Arbanon is considered to be the first sketch of an Albanian state, which retained a semi-autonomous status as the western extremity of the Byzantine Empire, under the Byzantine Doukai of Epirus or Laskarids of Nicaea.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Towards the end of the 12th and beginning of the 13th centuries, Serbs and Venetians began to take possession of the territory.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The ethnogenesis of the Albanians is uncertain; however, the first undisputed mention of Albanians dates back in historical records from 1079 or 1080 in a work by Michael Attaleiates, who referred to the Albanoi as having taken part in a revolt against Constantinople.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] At this point, the Albanians were fully Christianised.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] After the dissolution of Arbanon, Charles I of Anjou concluded an agreement with the Albanian rulers, promising to protect them and their ancient liberties.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 1272, he established the Kingdom of Albania and conquered regions back from the Despotate of Epirus.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The kingdom claimed all of central Albania territory from Dyrrhachium along the Adriatic Sea coast down to Butrint.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] A Catholic political structure was a basis for the papal plans of spreading Catholicism in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] This plan also found the support of Helen of Anjou.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Around 30 Catholic churches and monasteries were built during her rule, mainly in northern Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Internal power struggles within the Byzantine Empire in the 14th century enabled Serbs' most powerful medieval ruler, Stefan Dušan, to establish a short-lived empire that included all of Albania except Durrës.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 1367, Albanian rulers established the Despotate of Arta.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] During that time, several Albanian principalities were established, notably the Principality of Albania, the Principality of Kastrioti, the Lordship of Berat, and the Principality of Dukagjini.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In the first half of the 15th century, the Ottoman Empire invaded most of Albania, and the League of Lezhë was organized under Skanderbeg as a ruler, who became the national hero of the Albanian medieval history.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] that halted Ottoman advance into Europe for 25 years.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] With the fall of Constantinople, the Ottoman Empire entered an extended period of military conquest and expansion, with its borders gradually expanding deep into Southeast Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 1385, they reached the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, while in 1415, they established their garrisons across Southern Albania, eventually occupying most of Albania in 1431.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Thousands of Albanians consequently fled to Western Europe, particularly to Calabria, Naples, Ragusa, and Sicily, while numerous others sought protection at the often inaccessible Mountains of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Since the vast majority of Albanians were adherents of Christianity, they were considered an inferior class of people, resulting in them being discriminated against in various forms, including being subjected to heavy taxes.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Additionally, the Devshirme system allowed the Sultan to collect a requisite percentage of Christian adolescents from their families to compose the Janissary.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Ottoman conquest was also accompanied by the gradual process of Islamisation and the rapid construction of mosques.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] A prosperous and longstanding revolution erupted after the formation of the League of Lezhë until the fall of Shkodër under the leadership of Gjergj Kastrioti Skanderbeg, who consistently defeated major Ottoman armies led by Sultans Murad II and Mehmed II.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Skanderbeg managed to unite several of the Albanian principalities, amongst them the Arianitis, Dukagjinis, Zaharias, and Thopias, and establish a centralised authority over most of the non-conquered territories, becoming the Lord of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Despite his competence as a military leader, Skanderbeg's victories over the Ottoman Empire's military had only a short-term impact, as his forces were unable to halt the Ottomans' advancement permanently; therefore, they successfully delayed the final conquest of Albanian lands only temporarily.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The constant Ottoman invasions caused enormous destruction to Albania, greatly reducing the population and destroying flocks of livestock and crops.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Besides surrender, there was no possible way Skanderbeg would be able to halt the Ottoman invasions despite his military forces achieving several consecutive victories against them.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Among other factors, his manpower and resources were insufficient for a prolonged war, preventing him from expanding the war efforts and driving the Turks from the Albanian borders.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania was therefore doomed to face an unending series of Ottoman attacks until it eventually fell years after his death.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] When the Ottomans were gaining a firm foothold in the region, Albanian towns were organised into four principal sanjaks.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The government fostered trade by settling a sizeable Jewish colony of refugees fleeing persecution in Spain.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The city of Vlorë saw passing through its ports imported merchandise from Europe, such as velvets, cotton goods, mohairs, carpets, spices, and leather from Bursa and Constantinople.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Some citizens of Vlorë even had business associates throughout Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The phenomenon of Islamisation among the Albanians became primarily widespread from the 17th century and continued into the 18th century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Islam offered them equal opportunities and advancement within the Ottoman Empire.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] However, according to some scholars, motives for conversion were diverse depending on the context; although the lack of source material significantly hampers efforts to investigate such issues.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] As a result of the Ottomans' increasing suppression of Catholicism, most Catholic Albanians converted in the 17th century, while Orthodox Albanians followed suit mainly in the following century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Since the Albanian-inhabited regions were considered strategically important, Albanians made up a significant proportion of the Ottoman Empire's military and bureaucracy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Consequently, many Muslim Albanians attained important political and military positions, while their work made a significant cultural contribution to the broader Muslim world.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Enjoying this privileged position, they held various high administrative positions, which, among others, included over two dozen Albanians serving as Grand viziers of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Additionally, other distinguished Albanians included members of the prominent Köprülü family, Zagan Pasha, Muhammad Ali of Egypt, and Ali Pasha of Tepelena.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Furthermore, two Ottoman sultans, Bayezid II and Mehmed III, were born to mothers of Albanian ethnic backgrounds.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Albanian Renaissance was a period with its roots in the late 18th century and continuing into the 19th century, during which the Albanian people gathered spiritual and intellectual strength for an independent cultural and political life within an independent nation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Modern Albanian culture flourished too, especially Albanian literature and arts, and was frequently linked to the influences of the Romanticism and Enlightenment principles.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Prior to the rise of nationalism, Ottoman authorities suppressed any expression of national unity or conscience by the Albanian people.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The victory of Russia over the Ottoman Empire following the Russian-Ottoman Wars resulted the execution of the Treaty of San Stefano which assigned Albanian-populated lands to their Slavic and Greek neighbours.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] However, the United Kingdom and Austro-Hungarian Empire consequently blocked the arrangement and caused the Treaty of Berlin.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] From this point, Albanians started to organise themselves with the goal to protect and unite the Albanian-populated lands into a unitary nation, leading to the formation of the League of Prizren.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The league had initially the assistance of the Ottoman authorities whose position was based on the religious solidarity of Muslim people and landlords connected with the Ottoman administration.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] They favoured and protected the Muslim solidarity and called for defence of Muslim lands simultaneously constituting the reason for titling the league Committee of the Real Muslims.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Approximately 300 Muslims participated in the assembly composed by delegates from Bosnia, the administrator of the Sanjak of Prizren as representatives of the central authorities and no delegates from Vilayet of Scutari.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Ottomans authorities cancelled their assistance when the league, under Abdyl Frashëri, became focused on working towards Albanian autonomy and requested merging four vilayets, including Kosovo, Shkodër, Monastir and Ioannina, into a unified vilayet, the Albanian Vilayet.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The league used military force to prevent the annexing areas of Plav and Gusinje assigned to Montenegro.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] After several successful battles with Montenegrin troops, such as the Battle of Novšiće, the league was forced to retreat from their contested regions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The league was later defeated by the Ottoman army sent by the sultan.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania declared independence from the Ottoman Empire on 28 November 1912, accompanied by the establishment of the Senate and Government by the Assembly of Vlorë on 4 December 1912.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Its sovereignty was recognised by the Conference of London.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] On 29 July 1913, the Treaty of London delineated the borders of the country and its neighbors, leaving many Albanians outside Albania, predominantly partitioned between Montenegro, Serbia, and Greece.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Headquartered in Vlorë, the International Commission of Control was established on 15 October 1913 to take care of the administration of Albania until its own political institutions were in order.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The International Gendarmerie was established as the Principality of Albania's first law enforcement agency.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In November, the first gendarmerie members arrived in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Prince of Albania Wilhelm of Wied *(Princ Vilhelm Vidi)* was selected as the first prince of the principality.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] On 7 March, he arrived in the provisional capital of Durrës and began to organise his government, appointing Turhan Pasha Përmeti to form the first Albanian cabinet.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In November 1913, the Albanian pro-Ottoman forces had offered the throne of Albania to the Ottoman war minister of Albanian origin, Ahmed Izzet Pasha.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The pro-Ottoman peasants believed that the new regime was a tool of the six Christian Great Powers and local landowners, who owned half of the arable land.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In February 1914, the Autonomous Republic of Northern Epirus was proclaimed in Gjirokastër by the local Greek population against incorporation to Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] This initiative was short-lived, and in 1921 the southern provinces were incorporated into the Albanian Principality.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] High-ranking Orthodox clergy were among the strongest opponents of the Albanian National Awakening.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Reports from the period, including those from international observers, documented the burning of villages and civilian casualties.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Nationalist Orthodox insurgents were accused of targeting Muslim Albanian populations to consolidate territorial claims for Greece.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Meanwhile, the revolt of Albanian peasants against the new regime erupted under the leadership of the group of Muslim clerics gathered around Essad Pasha Toptani, who proclaimed himself the savior of Albania and Islam.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] To gain the support of the Mirdita Catholic volunteers from northern Albania, Prince Wied appointed their leader, Prênk Bibë Doda, foreign minister of the Principality of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In May and June 1914, the International Gendarmerie was joined by Isa Boletini and his men, mostly from Kosovo, and the rebels defeated northern Mirdita Catholics, capturing most of Central Albania by the end of August 1914.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Prince Wied's regime collapsed, and he left the country on 3 September 1914.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The interwar period in Albania was marked by persistent economic and social difficulties, political instability and foreign interventions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] After World War I, Albania lacked an established government and internationally recognised borders, rendering it vulnerable to neighboring entities such as Greece, Italy, and Yugoslavia, all of which sought to expand their influence.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] This led to political uncertainty, highlighted in 1918 when the Congress of Durrës sought Paris Peace Conference protection but was denied, further complicating Albania's position on the international stage.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Territorial tensions escalated as Yugoslavia, particularly Serbia, sought control of northern Albania, while Greece aimed dominance in southern Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The situation deteriorated in 1919 when the Serbs launched attacks on Albanian inhabitants, among others in Gusinje and Plav, resulting in massacres and large-scale displacement.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Meanwhile, Italian influence continued to expand during this time, driven by economic interests and political ambitions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Fan Noli, renowned for his idealism, became prime minister in 1924, with a vision to institute a Western-style constitutional government, abolish feudalism, counter Italian influence, and enhance critical sectors, including infrastructure, education and healthcare.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] He faced resistance from former allies, who had assisted in the removal of Zog from power, and struggled to secure foreign aid to implement his agenda.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Noli's decision to establish diplomatic ties with the Soviet Union, an adversary of the Serbian elite, ignited allegations of bolshevism from Belgrade.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] This in turn led to increased pressure from Italy and culminated in Zog's restoration to authority.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 1928, Zog transitioned Albania from a republic to a monarchy that garnered backing from Fascist Italy, with Zog assuming the title of King Zog I.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Key constitutional changes dissolved the Senate and established a unicameral National Assembly while preserving Zog's authoritative powers.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 1939, Italy under Benito Mussolini launched a military invasion of Albania, resulting in the exile of Zog and the creation of an Italian protectorate.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] As World War II progressed, Italy aimed to expand its territorial dominion in the Balkans, including territorial claims on regions of Greece (Chameria), Macedonia, Montenegro and Kosovo.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] These ambitions laid the foundation of Greater Albania, which aimed to unite all areas with Albanian-majority populations into a single country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 1943, as Italy's control declined, Nazi Germany assumed control of Albania, subjecting Albanians to forced labour, economic exploitation and repression under German rule.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] This period saw the forced expulsion and massacres of the Cham Albanians, a predominantly Muslim group.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The religious divide was used as a justification for violence, with some Orthodox locals reportedly identifying Muslim neighbors to paramilitary groups, leading to massacres and the forced expulsion of thousands.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The tide shifted in 1944 when Albanian partisan forces, under the leadership of Enver Hoxha and other communist leaders, successfully liberated Albania from German occupation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The establishment of the People's Republic of Albania under the leadership of Enver Hoxha was a significant epoch in modern Albanian history.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Hoxha's regime embraced Marxist–Leninist ideologies and implemented authoritarian policies, including prohibition of religious practices, severe restrictions on travel, and abolition of private property rights.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] It was also defined by a persistent pattern of purges, extensive repression, instances of betrayal, and hostility to external influences.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Any form of opposition or resistance to his rule was met with expeditious and severe consequences, such as internal exile, extended imprisonment, and execution.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The regime confronted a multitude of challenges, including widespread poverty, illiteracy, health crises and gender inequality.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In response, Hoxha initiated a modernisation initiative aimed at attaining economic and social liberation and transforming Albania into an industrial society.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania's diplomatic history under Hoxha was characterised by notable conflicts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Initially aligned with Yugoslavia as a satellite state, the relationship deteriorated as Yugoslavia aimed to incorporate Albania within its territory.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Subsequently, Albania established relations with the Soviet Union and engaged trade agreements with other Eastern European countries, but experienced disagreements over Soviet policies, leading to strained ties with Moscow and diplomatic separation in 1961.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Simultaneously, tensions with the West heightened due to Albania's refusal to hold free elections and allegations of Western support for anti-communist uprisings.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania's enduring partnership was with China; it sided with Beijing during the Sino-Soviet conflict, resulting in severed ties with the Soviet Union and withdrawal from the Warsaw Pact in response to the invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] But their relations stagnated in 1970, prompting both to reassess their commitment, and Albania actively reduced its dependence on China.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Under Hoxha's regime, Albania underwent a widespread campaign targeting religious clergy of various faiths, resulting in public persecution and executions, particularly targeting Muslims, Roman Catholics and Eastern Orthodox adherents.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 1946, religious estates underwent nationalisation, coinciding with the closure or transformation of religious institutions into various other purposes.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] This culminated in 1976, when Albania became the world's first constitutionally atheist state.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Under this regime, citizens were forced to renounce their religious beliefs, adopt a secular way of life, and embrace socialist ideology.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] After four decades of communism paired with the revolutions of 1989, Albania witnessed a notable rise in political activism, particularly among students, which led to a transformation in the prevailing order.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] After the first multi-party elections of 1991, the communist party maintained a stronghold in the parliament until its defeat in the parliamentary elections of 1992 directed by the Democratic Party.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Considerable economic and financial resources were devoted to pyramid schemes that were widely supported by the government.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The schemes swept up somewhere between one sixth and one third of the population of the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Despite the International Monetary Fund's warnings, Sali Berisha defended the schemes as large investment firms, leading more people to redirect their remittances and sell their homes and cattle for cash to deposit in the schemes.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The schemes began to collapse in late 1996, leading many of the investors to join initially peaceful protests against the government, requesting their money back.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The protests turned violent in February 1997 as government forces responded by firing on the demonstrators.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In March, the Police and Republican Guard deserted, leaving their armories open.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] These were promptly emptied by militias and criminal gangs.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The resulting civil war caused a wave of evacuations of foreign nationals and refugees.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The crisis led both Aleksandër Meksi and Sali Berisha to resign from office in the wake of the general election.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In April 1997, Operation Alba, a U.N. peacekeeping force led by Italy, entered Albania with two goals: to assist with the evacuation of expatriates and secure the ground for international organisations.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The main international organisation involved was the Western European Union's multinational Albanian Police element, which worked with the government to restructure the judicial system and simultaneously the Albanian police.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] After its communist system disintegrated, Albania embarked on an active path towards Westernisation with the ambition to obtain membership in the European Union (EU) and the North Atlantic Treaty Organisation (NATO).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] A notable milestone was reached in 2009, when the country attained membership in NATO, marking a pioneering achievement among the nations of Southeast Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In adherence to its vision for further integration into the EU, it formally applied for membership on 28 April 2009.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Another milestone was reached on 24 June 2014, when the country was granted official candidate status.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Edi Rama of the Socialist Party won both the 2013 and 2017 parliamentary elections.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] As prime minister, he implemented numerous reforms focused on modernising the economy, as well as democratising state institutions, including the judiciary and law enforcement.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Unemployment has steadily declined, with Albania achieving the 4th-lowest unemployment rate in the Balkans.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Rama has also placed gender equality at the centre of his agenda; since 2017 almost 50% of the ministers have been female, the largest number of women serving in the country's history.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] During the 2021 parliamentary elections, the ruling Socialist Party led by Rama secured its third consecutive victory, winning nearly half of votes and enough seats in parliament to govern alone.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] On 26 November 2019, a 6.4 magnitude earthquake ravaged Albania, with the epicentre about 16 km (10 mi) southwest of the town of Mamurras.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The tremor was felt in Tirana and in places as far away as Taranto, Italy, and Belgrade, Serbia, while the most affected areas were the coastal city of Durrës and the village of Kodër-Thumanë.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Comprehensive response to the earthquake included substantial humanitarian aid from the Albanian diaspora and various countries around the world.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] On 9 March 2020, COVID-19 was confirmed to have spread to Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] From March to June 2020, the government declared a state of emergency as a measure to limit the virus's spread.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The country's COVID-19 vaccination campaign started on 11 January 2021, but as of 11 August 2021, the total number of vaccines administered in Albania was 1,280,239 doses.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania lies along the Mediterranean Sea on the Balkan Peninsula in South and Southeast Europe, and has an area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] It is bordered by the Adriatic Sea to the west, Montenegro to the northwest, Kosovo to the northeast, North Macedonia to the east, Greece to the south, and the Ionian Sea to the southwest.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] It is between latitudes 42° and 39° N and longitudes 21° and 19° E.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Geographic coordinates include Vërmosh at 42° 35' 34" northern latitude as the northernmost point, Konispol at 39° 40' 0" northern latitude as the southernmost, Sazan at 19° 16' 50" eastern longitude as the westernmost, and Vërnik at 21° 1' 26" eastern longitude as the easternmost.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Mount Korab, rising at 2,764 m (9,068.24 ft) above the Adriatic, is the highest point, while the Mediterranean Sea, at 0 m (0.00 ft), is the lowest.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The country extends 148 km (92 mi) from east to west and around 340 km (211 mi) from north to south.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania has a diverse and varied landscape with mountains and hills that traverse its territory in various directions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The country is home to extensive mountain ranges, including the Albanian Alps in the north, the Korab Mountains in the east, the Pindus Mountains in the southeast, the Ceraunian Mountains in the southwest, and the Skanderbeg Mountains in the centre.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In the northwest is the Lake of Shkodër, Southern Europe's largest lake.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Towards the southeast emerges the Lake of Ohrid, one of the world's oldest continuously existing lakes.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Farther south, the expanse includes the Large and Small Lake of Prespa, some of the Balkans' highest lakes.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Rivers rise mostly in the east and discharge into the Adriatic and Ionian Seas.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The country's longest river, measured from mouth to source, is the Drin, which starts at the confluence of its two headwaters, the Black and White Drin.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Of particular concern is the Vjosë, one of Europe's last intact large river systems.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In Albania forest cover is around 29.% of the total land area, equivalent to 788,900 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, up from 788,800 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 11% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] For the year 2015, 97% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership, 3% private ownership and 0% with ownership listed as other or unknown.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The climate of Albania exhibits a distinguished level of variability and diversity due to the differences in latitude, longitude and altitude.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania experiences a Mediterranean and Continental climate, characterised by the presence of four distinct seasons.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] According to the Köppen classification, Albania encompasses five primary climatic types, spanning from Mediterranean and subtropical in the western half to oceanic, continental and subarctic in the eastern half of the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The coastal regions along the Adriatic and Ionian Seas in Albania are acknowledged as the warmest areas, while the northern and eastern regions encompassing the Albanian Alps and the Korab Mountains are recognised as the coldest areas in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Throughout the year, the average monthly temperatures fluctuate, ranging from −1 °C (30 °F) during the winter months to 21.8 °C (71.2 °F) in the summer months.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Notably, the highest recorded temperature of 43.9 °C (111.0 °F) was observed in Kuçovë on 18 July 1973, while the lowest temperature of −29 °C (−20 °F) was recorded in Shtyllë, Librazhd on 9 January 2017.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania receives most of the precipitation in winter months and less in summer months.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The average precipitation is about 1,485 millimetres (58.5 inches).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The mean annual precipitation ranges between 600 and 3,000 millimetres (24 and 118 inches) depending on geographical location.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The northwestern and southeastern highlands receive the intenser amount of precipitation, whilst the northeastern and southwestern highlands as well as the Western Lowlands the more limited amount.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The Albanian Alps in the far north of the country are considered to be among the most humid regions of Europe, receiving at least 3,100 mm (122.0 in) of rain annually.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Four glaciers within these mountains were discovered at a relatively low altitude of 2,000 metres (6,600 ft), which is extremely rare for such a southerly latitude.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] A biodiversity hotspot, Albania possesses an exceptionally rich and contrasting biodiversity on account of its geographical location at the centre of the Mediterranean Sea and the great diversity in its climatic, geological and hydrological conditions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The estuaries, wetlands and lakes are extraordinarily important for the greater flamingo, pygmy cormorant and the extremely rare and perhaps the most iconic bird of the country, the dalmatian pelican.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Of particular importance are the Mediterranean monk seal, loggerhead sea turtle and green sea turtle that use to nest on the country's coastal waters and shores.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In terms of phytogeography, Albania is part of the Boreal Kingdom and stretches specifically within the Illyrian province of the Circumboreal and Mediterranean Region.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Its territory can be subdivided into four terrestrial ecoregions of the Palearctic realm namely within the Illyrian deciduous forests, Balkan mixed forests, Pindus Mountains mixed forests and Dinaric Mountains mixed forests.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Approximately 3,500 different species of plants can be found in Albania which refers principally to a Mediterranean and Eurasian character.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The country maintains a vibrant tradition of herbal and medicinal practices.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] At the minimum 300 plants growing locally are used in the preparation of herbs and medicines.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The trees within the forests are primarily fir, oak, beech and pine.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania has been an active participant in numerous international agreements and conventions aimed at strengthing its commitment to the preservation and sustainable management of biological diversity.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Since 1994, the country is a party to the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) and its associated Cartagena and Nagoya Protocols.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] To uphold these commitments, it has developed and implemented a comprehensive National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan (NBSAP).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Furthermore, Albania has established a partnership with the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), advancing its conservation efforts on both national and international scales.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Guided by the IUCN, the country has made substantial progress in the foundation of protected areas within its boundaries, encompassing 12 national parks among others Butrint, Karaburun-Sazan, Llogara, Prespa and Vjosa.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] As a signatory to the Ramsar Convention, Albania has granted special recognition upon four wetlands, designating them as Wetlands of International Importance, including Buna-Shkodër, Butrint, Karavasta and Prespa.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The country's dedication to protection extends further into the sphere of UNESCO's World Network of Biosphere Reserves, operating within the framework of the Man and the Biosphere Programme, evidenced by its engagement in the Ohrid-Prespa Transboundary Biosphere Reserve.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Furthermore, Albania is host to two natural World Heritage Sites, which encompass the Ohrid region and both the Gashi River and Rrajca as part of Ancient and Primeval Beech Forests of the Carpathians and Other Regions of Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The protected areas of Albania are areas designated and managed by the Albanian government.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] There are 12 national parks, 4 ramsar sites, 1 biosphere reserve and 786 other types of conservation reserves in Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Located in the north, the Albanian Alps National Park, comprising the former Theth National Park and Valbonë Valley National Park, is surrounded amidst the towering peaks of the Albanian Alps.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In the east, portions of the rugged Korab, Nemërçka and Shebenik Mountains are conserved within the boundaries of Fir of Hotovë-Dangëlli National Park, Shebenik National Park and Prespa National Park, with the latter encompassing Albania's share of the Great and Small Lakes of Prespa.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] To the south, the Ceraunian Mountains define the Albanian Ionian Sea Coast, shaping the landscape of Llogara National Park, which extends into the Karaburun Peninsula, forming the Karaburun-Sazan Marine Park.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Further southward lies Butrint National Park, occupying a peninsula surrounded by the Lake of Butrint and the Channel of Vivari.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In the west, stretching along the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast, the Divjakë-Karavasta National Park boasts the extensive Lagoon of Karavasta, one of the largest lagoon systems in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Notably, Europe's first wild river national park, Vjosa National Park, safeguards the Vjosa River and its primary tributaries, which originates in the Pindus Mountains and flows to the Adriatic Sea.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Dajti Mountain National Park, Lurë-Dejë Mountain National Park and Tomorr Mountain National Park protect the mountainous terrain of the centre of Albania, including the Tomorr and Skanderbeg Mountains.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Environmental issues in Albania notably encompass air and water pollution, climate change impacts, waste management shortcomings, biodiversity loss and imperative for nature conservation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Climate change is predicted to exert significant impacts on the quality of life in Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania is one of the European countries most at risk and vulnerable to natural disasters.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Natural disasters, such as floods, forest fires, and landslides, are increasing in Albania due to climate change, causing significant damage.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Rising sea levels are anticipated to negatively impact coastal communities and the tourism industry.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] In 2023 Albania emitted 7.67 million tonnes of greenhouse gases, equivalent to 2.73 tonnes per person, making it a relatively low emitting country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] Albania has pledged a 20.9% reduction in GHG emissions by 2030, and net zero by 2050.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] The country has a moderate and improving performance in the Environmental Performance Index with an overall ranking of 62 out of 180 countries in 2022.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p01] However, Albania's ranking has decreased since its highest placement at position 15 in the Environmental Performance Index of 2012.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Since declaring independence in 1912, Albania has experienced a significant political transformation, traversing through distinct periods that included a monarchical rule, a communist regime and the eventual establishment of a democratic order.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 1998, Albania transitioned into a sovereign parliamentary constitutional republic, marking a fundamental milestone in its political evolution.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Its governance structure operates under a constitution that serves as the principal document of the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania's legal system is structured to protect its people's political rights, regardless of their ethnic, linguistic, racial, or religious affiliations.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Despite these principles, there are significant human rights concerns in Albania that demand attention.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] These concerns include issues related to the independence of the judiciary, the absence of a free media sector and the enduring problem of corruption within various governmental bodies, law enforcement agencies and other institutions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] As Albania pursues its path towards EU membership, active efforts are being made to achieve substantial improvements in these areas to align with EU criteria and standards.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Emerging from decades of isolation following the fall of communism, Albania has adopted a foreign policy orientation centred on active cooperation and engagement in international affairs.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The external affairs of Albania underscore the country's dedication to regional stability and integration into major international institutions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania became a member of the United Nations (UN) in 1955, shortly after emerging from a period of isolation during the communist era.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country reached a major achievement in its foreign policy by securing NATO membership in 2009.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Since obtaining candidate status in 2014, the country has also embarked on a comprehensive reform agenda to align itself with European Union (EU) accession standards, with the objective of becoming an EU member state.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania and Kosovo maintain a fraternal relationship strengthened by their substantial cultural, ethnical and historical ties.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Both countries foster enduring diplomatic ties, with Albania actively supporting Kosovo's development and international integration efforts.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Its fundamental contribution to Kosovo's path to independence is underscored by its early recognition of Kosovo's sovereignty in 2008.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Furthermore, both governments hold annual joint meetings, displayed by the inaugural meeting in 2014, which serves as an official platform to enhance bilateral cooperation and reinforce their joint commitment to policies that promote the stability and prosperity of the broader Albanian region.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Albanian Armed Forces consist of Land, Air and Naval Forces and constitute the military and paramilitary forces of the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] They are led by a commander-in-chief under the supervision of the Ministry of Defence and by the President as the supreme commander during wartime.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] However, in times of peace its powers are executed through the Prime Minister and the Defence Minister.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The chief purpose of the armed forces of Albania is the defence of the independence, the sovereignty and the territorial integrity of the country, as well as the participation in humanitarian, combat, non-combat and peace support operations.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Military service is voluntary since 2010 with the age of 19 being the legal minimum age for the duty.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania has committed to increase the participations in multinational operations.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Since the fall of communism, the country has participated in six international missions but only one United Nations mission in Georgia, where it sent three military observers.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Since February 2008, Albania has participated officially in NATO's Operation Active Endeavor in the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It was invited to join NATO on 3 April 2008, and it became a full member on 2 April 2009.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania reduced the number of active troops from 65,000 in 1988 to 14,500 in 2009.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The military now consists mainly of a small fleet of aircraft and sea vessels.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Increasing the military budget was one of the most important conditions for NATO integration.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] As of 1996 military spending was an estimated 1.5% of the country's GDP, only to peak in 2009 at 2% and fall again to 1.5%.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Nearly 60% of women in rural areas suffer physical or psychological violence and nearly 8% are victims of sexual violence.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2014 the Albanian Helsinki Committee (AHC) reported that the number of female murder victims is still high.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Commissioner for Protection from Discrimination has raised concerns regarding the family registration law that discriminates against women.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] As a result, heads of households, who are overwhelmingly men, have the right to change family residency without their partners' permission.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2015, the association ILGA-Europe ranked Albania 19th in terms of LGBT rights out of 49 observed European countries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] On the latest report in 2022, lack of progress caused Albania to be ranked the 28th country in Europe, among 49 countries observed.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] are the first-level administrative units in Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania is defined within a territorial area of 28,748 km2 (11,100 sq mi) in the Balkan Peninsula.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It is informally divided into three regions, the Northern, Central and Southern Regions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Since its Declaration of Independence in 1912, Albania has reformed its internal organisation 21 times.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Presently, the primary administrative units are the twelve constituent counties (*qarqe/qarqet*), which hold equal status under the law.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Counties had previously been used in the 1950s and were recreated on 31 July 2000 to unify the 36 districts (*rrathë/rrathët*) of that time.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The largest county in Albania by population is Tirana County with over 800,000 people.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The smallest county, by population, is Gjirokastër County with over 70,000 people.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The largest county, by area, is Korçë County encompassing 3,711 square kilometres (1,433 sq mi) of the southeast of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The smallest county, by area, is Durrës County with an area of 766 square kilometres (296 sq mi) in the west of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The counties are made up of 61 second-level divisions known as municipalities (*bashki/bashkia*).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The municipalities are the first level of local governance, responsible for local needs and law enforcement.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] They unified and simplified the previous system of urban and rural municipalities or communes (*komuna/komunat*) in 2015.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] For smaller issues of local government, the municipalities are organised into 373 administrative units (*njësia*/*njësitë administrative*).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] There are also 2980 villages (*fshatra/fshatrat*), neighborhoods or wards (*lagje/lagjet*), and localities (*lokalitete/lokalitetet*) previously used as administrative units.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Transitioning from a socialist planned to a capitalist mixed economy, Albania is classified as a developing open market with an upper-middle income status.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Albanian economy is characterised by a substantial service sector, comprising 48.6% of GDP, with key contributions from wholesale and retail trade, tourism, real estate, and logistics.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Following this, the industrial sector accounts for 20.2%, particularly influenced by construction, while the agricultural sector, including forestry, and fisheries, represents 18.5%, and the manufacturing sector contributes a modest 6.3% to the economy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] As of 2025, Albania's nominal gross domestic product (GDP) is reported at $26.911 billion with a GDP per capita of $9,474.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The projected annual percentage change in economic growth for 2025 is 3.8%, with a forecasted moderation to 3.5% by 2029.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania has developed a comprehensive framework for international trade through several pivotal agreements with various regions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Stabilisation and Association Agreement (SAA) with the European Union (EU), signed in 2006, is one of the most significant.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] This agreement provides critical trade benefits and serves as a foundation for the Albanian integration into the EU.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2009, Albania signed a free trade agreement (FTA) with the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), which further expands trade opportunities and market access.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country is also a signatory to the Central European Free Trade Agreement (CEFTA) and Organization of the Black Sea Economic Cooperation (BSEC), promoting regional trade and collaboration with neighboring countries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Furthermore, the country has enhanced its bilateral trade relations through a FTA with Turkey, the United Kingdom and a bilateral investment treaty with the United States.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The 2023 Economic Freedom of the World report placed Albania in the 31st position, noting a considerable degree of economic independence and the effective adoption of market-oriented policies.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The 2024 Bertelsmann Transformation Index ranked Albania 20th and acknowledged substantial progress in political and economic transformation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Also in 2024, the country was positioned 23rd in the Global Gender Gap Index, excelling in the Economic Participation and Opportunity category with a global ranking of 16th, showcasing significant advancements in women's economic participation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] However, the Albanian economy, despite demonstrating considerable resilience, encounters substantial vulnerabilities that hinder its development.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Principal challenges include widespread corruption, distorted competition, and frequent modifications to fiscal legislation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Furthermore, inadequate contract enforcement, a large informal sector, and persistent labor shortages further complicate the national economic progress.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Economic landscape of Albania is characterised by regional disparities, particularly apparent in the concentration of economic activities in the triangular region formed by Tirana, Durrës and Laç.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] This metropolitan area, referred to as Durana, functions as the principal economic center of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In the year 2021, Tirana County accounted for a significant 44% of the national GDP, with the counties of Fier and Durrës also playing integral roles in the economy, contributing 11% and 10% to the GDP, respectively.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Other substantial economic centers, such as Elbasan and the coastal cities of Sarandë and Vlorë, highlight the uneven distribution of economic development across the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Cultural regions, including Berat and Korçë, despite their geographical distance from the primary economic hubs, have derived considerable benefits from the expansion of the tourism sector.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Further, the country is a worldwide significant producer of salvia, rosemary and yellow gentian.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country's proximity to the Ionian Sea and the Adriatic Sea give the underdeveloped fishing industry great potential.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The World Bank and European Community economists report that, Albania's fishing industry has good potential to generate export earnings because prices in the nearby Greek and Italian markets are many times higher than those in the Albanian market.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The fish available off the coasts of the country are carp, trout, sea bream, mussels and crustaceans.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania has one of Europe's longest histories of viticulture.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Today's region was one of the few places where vine was naturally grown during the ice age.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The oldest found seeds in the region are 4,000 to 6,000 years old.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2009, the nation produced an estimated 17,500 tonnes of wine.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania's secondary sector has undergone many changes and diversification since the communist regime collapsed.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It is very diversified, from electronics, manufacturing, textiles, to food, cement, mining, and energy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Antea Cement plant in Fushë-Krujë is considered one of the nation's largest industrial greenfield investments.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albanian oil and gas is one of the most promising, albeit strictly regulated, sectors of its economy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania has the second-largest oil deposits in the Balkan peninsula after Romania, and the largest oil reserves in Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Albpetrol company is owned by the Albanian state and monitors the state petroleum agreements in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The textile industry has seen an extensive expansion by approaching companies from the European Union (EU) in Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] According to the Instituti i Statistikës (INSTAT), as of 2016, textile production had an annual growth of 5.3% and an annual turnover of around 1.5 billion euros.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania is a significant minerals producer and ranks among the world's leading chromium producers and exporters.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The nation is also a notable producer of copper, nickel, and coal.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Batra mine, Bulqizë mine, and Thekna mine are among the most recognised Albanian mines still in operation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The tertiary sector represents the fastest growing sector of the country's economy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] 36% of the population work in the service sector which contributes to 65% of the country's GDP.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Ever since the end of the 20th century, the banking industry is a major component of the tertiary sector and remains in good conditions overall due to privatisation and the commendable monetary policy.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Previously one of the most isolated and controlled countries in the world, telecommunication industry represents nowadays another major contributor to the sector.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It developed largely through privatisation and subsequent investment by both domestic and foreign investors.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Eagle, Vodafone and Telekom Albania are the leading telecommunications service providers in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Tourism is recognised as an industry of national importance and has been steadily increasing since the beginnings of the 21st century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It directly accounted for 8.4% of GDP in 2016 though including indirect contributions pushes the proportion to 26%.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In the same year, the country received approximately 4.74 million visitors mostly from across Europe and the United States as well.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The increase of foreign visitors has been dramatic.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania had only 500,000 visitors in 2005, and an estimated 4.2 million in 2012, an increase of 740 percent.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] According to the United Nations World Tourism Organization (UN Tourism), Albania welcomed approximately 11.7 million tourists in 2024, marking a significant increase from previous years.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The bulk of the tourist industry is concentrated along the Adriatic and Ionian Sea in the west of the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] But the Albanian Riviera in the southwest has the most scenic and pristine beaches; its coastline has a considerable length of 446 kilometres (277 miles).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The coast has a distinctive character, rich in varieties of virgin beaches, capes, coves, covered bays, lagoons, small gravel beaches, sea caves, and many landforms.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Some parts of this seaside are very clean ecologically, including unexplored areas, which are very rare within the Mediterranean.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Other attractions include the mountainous areas such as the Albanian Alps, Ceraunian Mountains and Korab Mountains but also the historical cities of Berat, Durrës, Gjirokastër, Sarandë, Shkodër and Korçë.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The international airport of Tirana is the premier air gateway to the country, and is also the principal hub for Albania's national flag carrier airline, Air Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The airport carried more than 3.3 million passengers in 2019 with connections to many destinations in other countries around Europe, Africa and Asia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country plans to progressively increase the number of airports especially in the south with possible locations in Sarandë, Gjirokastër and Vlorë.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The highways and motorways in Albania are properly maintained and often still under construction and renovation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Autostrada 1 (A1) is an integral transportation corridor and the country's longest motorway.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It is planned to link Durrës on the Adriatic Sea across Pristina in Kosovo with the Pan-European Corridor X in Serbia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Autostrada 2 (A2) is part of the Adriatic–Ionian Corridor as well as the Pan-European Corridor VIII and connects Fier with Vlorë.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Autostrada 3 (A3) is under construction and after its completion will connect Tirana and Elbasan with the Pan-European Corridor VIII.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] When all three corridors are completed, Albania will have an estimated 759 kilometres (472 mi) of highway, linking it with all neighboring countries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Durrës is the busiest and largest seaport in the country, followed by Vlorë, Shëngjin and Sarandë.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The rail network is administered by the national railway company Hekurudha Shqiptare.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] A new railway line from Tirana and its airport to Durrës is planned.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The location of this railway, connecting Albania's most populated urban areas, makes it an important economic development project.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Due to its location and natural resources, Albania has a wide variety of energy resources, ranging from gas, oil, and coal to wind, solar, water, and other renewable sources.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] According to the World Economic Forum's 2023 Energy Transition Index (ETI), the country ranked 21st globally, highlighting the progress in its energy transition agenda.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Currently, Albania's electricity generation sector depends on hydroelectricity, ranking fifth in the world in percentage terms.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Increasing risks of river floods and droughts due to climate change is expected to put electricity generation at risk.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Drin, in the north, hosts four hydroelectric power stations, including Fierza, Koman, Skavica and Vau i Dejës.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Two other power stations, such as the Banjë and Moglicë, are along the Devoll in the south.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It has the 10th-largest oil reserves in Europe and the 58th in the world.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country's main petroleum deposits are located around the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast and Myzeqe Plain within the Western Lowlands, where the country's largest reserve is located.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Patos-Marinza, also located within the area, is the largest onshore oil field in Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Trans Adriatic Pipeline (TAP), part of the planned Southern Gas Corridor, runs for 215 kilometres (134 miles) across Albania's territory before entering the Albanian Adriatic Sea Coast approximately 17 kilometres (11 miles) northwest of Fier.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania's water resources are particularly abundant in all the regions of the country and comprise lakes, rivers, springs, and groundwater aquifers.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country's available average quantity of fresh water is estimated at 129.7 cubic metres (4,580 cubic feet) per inhabitant per year, one of the highest rates in Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] According to data presented by the Joint Monitoring Programme for Water Supply and Sanitation (JMP) in 2015, about 93% of the country's total population had access to improved sanitation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The freedom of press and speech, and the right to free expression is guaranteed in the constitution of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania was ranked 84th on the Press Freedom Index of 2020 compiled by the Reporters Without Borders, with its score steadily declining since 2003.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Nevertheless, in the 2020 report of Freedom in the World, the Freedom House classified the freedoms of press and speech in Albania as partly free from political interference and manipulation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH) is the national broadcaster corporation of Albania operating numerous television and radio stations in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The three major private broadcaster corporations are Top Channel, Televizioni Klan and Vizion Plus whose content are distributed throughout Albania and beyond its territory in Kosovo and other Albanian-speaking territories.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albanian cinema has its roots in the 20th century and developed after the country's declaration of independence.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The first movie theater exclusively devoted to showing motion pictures was built in 1912 in Shkodër.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] During the People's Republic of Albania, Albanian cinema developed rapidly with the inauguration of the Kinostudio Shqipëria e Re in Tirana.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 1953, the Albanian-Soviet epic film, the Great Warrior Skanderbeg, was released chronicling the life and fight of the medieval Albanian hero Skanderbeg.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It went on to win the international prize at the 1954 Cannes Film Festival.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2003, the Tirana International Film Festival was established, the largest film festival in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Durrës Amphitheatre is host to the Durrës International Film Festival, the second largest film festival.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] After the fall of communism in 1991, human resources in sciences and technology in Albania have drastically decreased.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] As of various reports, during 1991 to 2005 approximately 50% of the professors and scientists of the universities and science institutions in the country have left Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania was ranked 67th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Telecommunication represents one of the fastest growing and dynamic sectors in Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Vodafone Albania, Telekom Albania and Albtelecom are the three large providers of mobile and internet in Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] As of the Electronic and Postal Communications Authority (AKEP) in 2018, the country had approximately 2.7 million active mobile users with almost 1.8 million active broadband subscribers.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Vodafone Albania alone served more than 931,000 mobile users, Telekom Albania had about 605,000 users and Albtelecom had more than 272,000 users.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In January 2023, Albania launched its first two satellites, *Albania 1* and *Albania 2*, into orbit, in what was regarded as a milestone effort in monitoring the country's territory and identifying illegal activities.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albanian-American engineer Mira Murati, the Chief Technology Officer of research organisation OpenAI, played a substantial role in the development and launch of artificial intelligence services such as ChatGPT, Codex and DALL-E.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In December 2023, Prime Minister Edi Rama announced plans for collaboration between the Albanian government and ChatGPT, facilitated by discussions with Murati.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Rama emphasised the intention to streamline the alignment of Albanian laws with the regulations of the European Union, aiming to reduce costs associated with translation and legal services.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The demographic statistics of Albania, as revealed by the 2023 census conducted by the Instituti i Statistikave (INSTAT), indicated a population of 2,402,113, with a notable decline from the 2,821,977 recorded in the 2011 census.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The decrease in inhabitants began after the disintegration of the communist regime in Albania and is associated with significant shifts within the political, economic, and social structure of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] A principal factor in this transition incorporates a decline in fertility rates coupled with an increase in emigration, both contributing to persistent demographic changes and challenges.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] It is forecast that the population will continue shrinking for the next decade at least, depending on the actual rates and the level of migration.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Currently, the population density of Albania is measured at 83.6 inhabitants per square kilometer with a varied distribution of inhabitants across different regions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The counties of Tirana and Durrës showcase substantial concentrations of people, accounting for about 41% of the overall demographic of Albania, with 32% residing in Tirana and 9% in Durrës.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Conversely, more peripheral and rural counties such as Gjirokastër and Kukës present significantly lower population densities, with each aiding 3% to the overall population.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Historically, the Albanian people have established several communities in many regions throughout Southern Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Albanian diaspora has been formed since the late Middle Ages, when they emigrated to escape either various socio-political difficulties or the Ottoman conquest of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Following the fall of communism, large numbers of Albanians have migrated to countries such as Australia, Canada, Switzerland, the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albanian minorities are present in the neighbouring territories such as the west of North Macedonia, the southeast of Montenegro, Kosovo in its entirety and parts of southern Serbia.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Altogether, the number of ethnic Albanians living abroad is estimated to be higher than the total population inside Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] As much as a third of those born in the country's borders now live outside of it, making Albania one of the countries with the highest rate of outmigration relative to its population in the world.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2022 the birth rate was 20% lower than in 2021, largely due to emigration of people of childbearing age.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Subsequent to the collapse of communism in 1991, Albania has undergone a remarkable transformation in its urban landscape, emerging as one of the fastest urbanising countries in Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] At the forefront of this transformation is the Tirana–Durrës agglomeration, a densely populated urban corridor situated along the western coast of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] This corridor has become the primary locus of population growth and settlement development, attracting a significant influx of internal migrants from the country's peripheral areas.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Despite an overall decline of the country's total population, the proportion of the urban demographic has consistently progressed from 47% in 2001 to 65% in 2023.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] This sustained increase, coupled with the concentration in the Tirana-Durrës region, has led to a spread of regional imbalances, with the peripheral areas, particularly Dibër and Kukës, experiencing severe depopulation.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The official language of the country is Albanian which is spoken by the vast majority of the country's population.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Its standard spoken and written form is revised and merged from the two main dialects, Gheg and Tosk, though it is notably based more on the Tosk dialect.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Shkumbin river is the rough dividing line between the two dialects.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Among minority languages, Greek is the second most-spoken language in the country, with 0.5 to 3% of the population speaking it as first language, mainly in the country's south where its speakers are concentrated.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Other languages spoken by ethnic minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Serbo-Croatian, Macedonian, Bulgarian, Gorani, and Roma.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Macedonian is official in the Pustec Municipality in East Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In the 2023 population census, 91.07% reported Albanian as the language spoken at home.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] 1.54% declared to speak at home another language, 0.57% multiple languages, 1.21% gave no answer and 5.59% were unavailable.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Among young people aged 25 or less, English, German and Turkish have seen rising interest after 2000.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Italian and French have had a stable interest, while Greek has lost much of its previous interest.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The trends are linked with cultural and economic factors.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In the mid-2010s, an increasing number of Albanians showed interest in learning the German language, which has been explained as part of "a Western Balkan trend of preparing to integrate into the German labor market".
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Some of them have gone to Germany for studies or work.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania and Germany have agreements for cooperating in helping young people of the two countries know both cultures better.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Due to a sharp rise in economic relations with Turkey, interest in learning Turkish, in particular among young people, was also growing on a yearly basis in the 2010s.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Designated national and cultural minorities in Albania include Aromanian, Greek, Macedonian, Montenegrin, Serb, Roma, Egyptian, Bosnian and Bulgarian peoples, as well as Gorani and Jews as other minority groups.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania is a secular and religiously diverse country with no official religion.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Freedom of religion, belief and conscience are guaranteed under the country's constitution.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania is nevertheless ranked among the least religious countries in the world.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Religion constitute an important role in the lives of only 39% of the country's population.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In another report, 56% considered themselves religious, 30% considered themselves non-religious, while 9% defined themselves as convinced atheists.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The Muslim Albanians are spread throughout the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Orthodox and Bektashis are mostly found in the south, whereas Catholics mainly live in the north.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2008, there were 694 Catholic churches and 425 Orthodox churches, 568 mosques and 70 bektashi takyas in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] During modern times, the Albanian republican, monarchic and later communist regimes followed a systematic policy of separating religion from official functions and cultural life.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country has never had an official religion either as a republic or as a kingdom.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In the 20th century, the clergy of all faiths was weakened under the monarchy and ultimately eradicated during the 1950s and 1960s, under the state policy of obliterating all organised religion from the territories of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The communist regime persecuted and suppressed religious observance and institutions and entirely banned religion.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country was then officially declared to be the world's first atheist state.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Religious freedom has returned, however, since the end of communism.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Islam survived communist era persecution and reemerged in the modern era as a practised religion in Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Some smaller Christian sects in Albania include Evangelicals and several Protestant communities including Seventh-day Adventist Church, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints and Jehovah's Witnesses.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The first recorded Protestant of Albania was Said Toptani, who travelled around Europe and returned to Tirana in 1853, where he preached Protestantism.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The first evangelical Protestants appeared in the 19th century and the Evangelical Alliance was founded in 1892.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Nowadays, it has 160 member congregations from different Protestant denominations.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Following mass emigration to Israel after the fall of communism, there are only 200 Albanian Jews left in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In Albania, education is secular, free, compulsory, and based on three levels.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The academic year is apportioned into two semesters, beginning in September or October and ending in June or July.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albanian is the primary language of instruction in the country's academic institutions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The study of a first foreign language is mandatory and taught most often at elementary and bilingual schools.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Languages taught in schools are English, Italian, French and German.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Albania has a school life expectancy of 16 years and a literacy rate of 98.7%, with 99.2% for men and 98.3% for women.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Compulsory primary education is divided into two levels, elementary and secondary school, from grade one to five and six to nine, respectively.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Pupils are required to attend school from the age six until they turn 16.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Upon successful completion of primary education, all pupils are entitled to attend high schools, specialising in any field, including arts, sports, languages, sciences, and technology.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Tertiary education is optional and has undergone a thorough reformation and restructuring in compliance with the principles of the Bologna Process.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] There are a significant number of private and public institutions of higher education in Albania's major cities.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Tertiary education is organised into three successive levels, the bachelor, master, and doctorate.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The constitution of Albania guarantees its citizens equal, free, and universal health care.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The health care system is organised into primary, secondary, and tertiary healthcare, and is in a process of modernisation and development.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The life expectancy at birth in Albania is 77.8 years, ranking 37th in the world and surpassing several developed countries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The average healthy life expectancy is 68.8 years, ranking 37th in the world.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] The country's infant mortality rate was estimated at 12 per 1,000 live births in 2015.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2000, the country had the world's 55th-best healthcare performance, as defined by the World Health Organisation (WHO).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Cardiovascular disease is the principal cause of death in Albania, accounting for 52% of deaths.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Accidents, injuries, malignant and respiratory diseases are other primary causes of death.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Neuropsychiatric disease has also increased due to recent demographic, social, and economic changes in the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] In 2009, Albania had a fruit and vegetable supply of 886 grams per capita per day, the fifth-highest supply in Europe.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] Compared to other developed and developing countries, Albania has a relatively low rate of obesity, probably thanks to the Mediterranean diet.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p02] According to 2016 WHO data, 21.7% of adults in the country are clinically overweight, with a Body mass index (BMI) score of 25 or more.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The red and black national colours are displayed on the flag of Albania that is adorned with a double-headed eagle as the foremost recognised national symbol of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] With the black eagle portraying bravery and strength, the red field symbolises the fortitude and sacrifices of the Albanian people.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The eagle is linked with the legacy of the national hero Gjergj Kastrioti, renowned as Skanderbeg, who led a prosperous resistance movement against Ottoman rule.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Rooted in the Middle Ages, it emerged as a heraldic symbol in the Principality of Arbër and among notable Albanian dynasties such as the Dukagjini, Kastrioti, Muzaka and Thopia clans.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Amid the Albanian Renaissance, marking the resurgence of Albanian national identity and aspirations for independence, the Albanian eagle regained its prominence.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Its importance reached its culmination with Albania's declaration of independence in 1912, when Ismail Qemali raised it as the national flag in Vlorë.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The coat of arms of Albania is an adaptation of the flag of Albania and the seal of Skanderbeg.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The coat comprises the black double-headed eagle positioned at the centre of a red field.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Above the eagle, it carries the helmet of Skanderbeg that is crowned with the head of a golden horned goat.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Ti Shqipëri, më jep nder, më jep emrin Shqipëtar, which translates to "You Albania, give me honour, give me the name Albanian", is the national motto of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] It finds its foundation in the legacy of national poet Naim Frashëri, who held a renowned role during the Albanian Renaissance.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The national anthem of Albania, "Himni i Flamurit", was composed by Asdreni and adopted as such following Albania's independence in 1912.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Albanian traditional clothing, with its contrasting variations for the northern Gheg and southern Tosk Albanians, is a testament to Albania's history, cultural diversity and ethnic identity.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Gheg men wear a light-colored shirt paired with wide loose-fitting trousers referred to as the Tirq.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] These trousers are securely fastened by a wide woven belt, the Brez.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] An integral component of their costume is the Xhamadan, a woolen red velvet vest adorned with folkloric motifs and gold patterns.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] They also wear a distinctive dome-shaped hat known as the Qeleshe, crafted from wool, with its origins tracing back to the Illyrians.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Conversely, Tosk men opt for the Fustanella, a knee-length garment designated as the national costume, typically white with pleats, accompanied by a white shirt.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] They also wear a beige or dark blue Xhamadan reminiscent of the Gheg attire.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] To complete their attire, men wear knee-high socks referred to as Çorape and leather shoes known as Opinga.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The attire of Gheg and Tosk women is renowned for its rich palette of colors and intricate filigree detailing, displayed across various components including ear ornaments, finger rings, necklaces, belt buckles and buttons.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Key components include a long, light-toned shirt paired with an apron, often accompanied by a woolen or felt mantle referred to as the Xhoka.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Additional upper garments, such as the Dollama or Mintan, may be layered, along with a headscarf known as Kapica or Shall.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] A distinctive variation incorporates a pair of aprons, including the Pështjellak at the rear and the Paranik at the front.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Integral to the traditional attire of Gheg women is the ancient Xhubleta.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Dedicated efforts have been undertaken to preserve and promote the dress, acknowledging its significance as an emblem of Albanian heritage.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] As a testament to its importance, the Xhubleta has been inscribed on the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage List.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The distinctive bell-shaped garment is fashioned in black and enriched with embroidered ethnic Albanian motifs, showcasing the remarkable craftsmanship of northern Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Its crafting process involves multiple intricate stages, encompassing the preparation of shajak fabric and the precise cutting techniques.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The artistic history of Albania has been particularly influenced by a multitude of ancient and medieval people, traditions and religions.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] It covers a broad spectrum with mediums and disciplines that include painting, pottery, sculpture, ceramics and architecture all of them exemplifying a great variety in style and shape, in different regions and period.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The rise of the Byzantine and Ottoman Empire in the Middle Ages was accompanied by a corresponding growth in Christian and Islamic art in the lands of Albania which are apparent in examples of architecture and mosaics throughout the country.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Centuries later, the Albanian Renaissance proved crucial to the emancipation of the modern Albanian culture and saw unprecedented developments in all fields of literature and art whereas artists sought to return to the ideals of Impressionism and Romanticism.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] However, Onufri, Kolë Idromeno, David Selenica, Kostandin Shpataraku and the Zografi Brothers are the most eminent representatives of Albanian art.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The architecture of Albania reflects the legacy of various civilisations tracing back to the classical antiquity.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Major cities in Albania have evolved from within the castle to include dwellings, religious and commercial structures, with constant redesigning of town squares and evolution of building techniques.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Nowadays, the cities and towns reflect a whole spectrum of various architectural styles.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] In the 20th century, many historical as well as sacred buildings bearing the ancient influence were demolished during the communist era.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Ancient architecture is found throughout Albania and most visible in Byllis, Amantia, Phoenice, Apollonia, Butrint, Antigonia, Shkodër and Durrës.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Considering the long period of rule of the Byzantine Empire, they introduced castles, citadels, churches and monasteries with spectacular wealth of visible murals and frescos.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Perhaps the best known examples can be found in the southern Albanian cities and surroundings of Korçë, Berat, Voskopojë and Gjirokastër.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Involving the introduction of Ottoman architecture there was a development of mosques and other Islamic buildings, particularly seen in Berat and Gjirokastër.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] A productive period of Historicism, Art Nouveau and Neoclassicism merged into the 19th century, best exemplified in Korçë.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The 20th century brought new architectural styles such as the modern Italian style, which is present in Tirana such as the Skanderbeg Square and Ministries.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] It is also present in Shkodër, Vlorë, Sarandë and Durrës.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Moreover, other towns received their present-day Albania-unique appearance through various cultural or economic influences.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Socialist classicism arrived during the communist era in Albania after the Second World War.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] At this period many socialist-styled complexes, wide roads and factories were constructed, while town squares were redesigned and numerous of historic and important buildings demolished.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Notable examples of that style include the Mother Teresa Square, Pyramid of Tirana, Palace of Congresses and so on.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Three Albanian archaeological sites are included in the list of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] These include the ancient remains of Butrint, the medieval Historic Centres of Berat and Gjirokastër, and Natural and Cultural Heritage of the Ohrid region site shared with North Macedonia since 2019.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Furthermore, the royal Illyrian tombs, the remains of Apollonia, the ancient Amphitheatre of Durrës and the Fortress of Bashtovë has been included on the tentative list of Albania.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Albanian folk music is a prominent part of the national identity, and continues to play a major part in overall Albanian music.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Folk music can be divided into two stylistic groups, mainly the northern Gheg varieties, and southern Lab and Tosk varieties.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Northern and southern traditions are contrasted by a rugged tone from the north, and the more relaxed southern form of music.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Many songs concern events from Albanian history and culture, including traditional themes of honour, hospitality, treachery, and revenge.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The first compilation of Albanian folk music was made by two Himariot musicians, Neço Muka and Koço Çakali, in Paris, during their work with Albanian soprano Tefta Tashko-Koço.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Several gramophone compilations were recorded at the time by the three artists, which eventually led to the recognition of Albanian iso-polyphony as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Festivali i Këngës is a traditional Albanian song contest organised by the national broadcaster Radio Televizioni Shqiptar (RTSH).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The festival is celebrated annually since its inauguration in 1962 and has launched the careers of some of Albania's most successful singers including Vaçe Zela and Parashqevi Simaku.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] It is significantly a music competition among Albanian performers presenting unreleased songs in premiere, composed by Albanian authors and voted by juries or by public.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Contemporary artists Rita Ora, Bebe Rexha, Era Istrefi, Dua Lipa, Ava Max, Bleona, Elvana Gjata, Ermonela Jaho, and Inva Mula have achieved international recognition for their music, while soprano Ermonela Jaho has been described by some as the "world's most acclaimed soprano".
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Albanian opera singer Saimir Pirgu was nominated for the 2017 Grammy Award.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The cultural renaissance was first of all expressed through the development of the Albanian language in the area of church texts and publications.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The Protestant reforms invigorated hopes for the development of the local language and literary tradition, when cleric Gjon Buzuku translated the Catholic liturgy into Albanian, trying to do for Albanian what Martin Luther had done for German.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Meshari (*The Missal*) written by Gjon Buzuku was published in 1555 and is considered one of the first literary work of written Albanian during the Middle Ages.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The refined level of the language and the stabilised orthography must be the result of an earlier tradition of written Albanian, a tradition that is not well understood.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] However, there is some fragmented evidence, pre-dating Buzuku, which indicates that Albanian was written from at least the 14th century.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Albanian writings from these centuries must not have been religious texts only, but historical chronicles too.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The *History of Skanderbeg* is still the foundation of Skanderbeg studies and is considered an Albanian cultural treasure, vital to the formation of Albanian national self-consciousness.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] The most famous Albanian writer in the 20th and 21st century is probably Ismail Kadare.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Throughout the centuries, Albanian cuisine has been widely influenced by Albanian culture, geography and history, and as such, different parts of the country enjoy specific regional cuisines.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Cooking traditions especially vary between the north and the south, owing to differing topography and climate that essentially contribute to the excellent growth conditions for a wide array of herbs, fruits, and vegetables.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Albanians produce and use many varieties of fruits such as lemons, oranges, figs, and most notably, olives, which are perhaps the most important element of Albanian cooking.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Spices and other herbs such as basil, lavender, mint, oregano, rosemary, and thyme are widely used, as are vegetables such as garlic, onions, peppers, potatoes, tomatoes, as well as legumes of all types.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] With a coastline along the Adriatic and Ionian in the Mediterranean Sea, fish, crustaceans, and seafood are a popular and an integral part of the Albanian diet.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Otherwise, lamb is the traditional meat for different holidays and religious festivals for both Christians and Muslims, although poultry, beef, and pork are also in plentiful supply.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Tavë kosi ("soured milk casserole") is the national dish of Albania, consisting of lamb and rice baked under a thick, tart veil of yoghurt.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Fërgesë is another national dish, made up of peppers, tomatoes, and cottage cheese.
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Pite is also popular, a baked pastry with a filling of a mixture of spinach and gjizë (curd) or mish (ground meat).
[src:international-electrotechnical-commission/albania-p03] Petulla, a traditional fried dough, is also a popular speciality, and is served with powdered sugar or feta cheese and different sorts of fruit jams.
